"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757835","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of complaints about Personal Independence Payments is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Tier One complaints – A total of 6292 complaints were cleared, of which 165 took longer than 20 working days to receive a response</p><p> </p><p>Tier Two complaints - A total of 170 complaints were cleared, of which 30 took longer than 20 working days to receive a response.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>(Data provided for complaints closed within the 2016/2017 operational year)</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-13T11:16:05.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757835/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757835/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Personal Independence Payment: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) tier one and (b) tier two complaints relating to personal independence payments take longer than 20 working days to receive a response.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757836","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of complaints about Personal Independence Payments which took more than 15 working days but less than 20 working days to receive a response is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Tier One complaints - A total of 6292 complaints were cleared, of which 132 received a response which took more than 15 working days but less than 20 working days</p><p> </p><p>Tier Two complaints - A total of 170 complaints were cleared, of which 24 received a response which took more than 15 working days but less than 20 working days</p><p> </p><p>(Data provided for complaints closed within the 2016/2017 operational year)</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-13T11:14:28.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757836/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757836/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Personal Independence Payment: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) tier one and (b) tier two complaints relating to personal independence payments are responded to in more than 15 but less than 20 days.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757837","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p><p>HM Revenue and Customs members of staff do not work on processing Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims, instead DWP has responsibility for processing PIP claims.</p>The table below shows the Full Time Equivalent (FTE) number of DWP staff working on processing PIP claims for each of the years 2013/14, 2014/15, 2015/16 and 2016/17</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP Claims FTE</p></td><td><p>418.9</p></td><td><p>865.3</p></td><td><p>786.9</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP Claims inc Training FTE*</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>774.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>*ABM definition changed for this work from 2016/17</p><p>Source: OPS ABM FTE (L1A)</p><p>Data extracted 7/9/17</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-13T11:44:25.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757837/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757837/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many members of staff in HM Revenue and Customs worked on processing personal independence payment claims in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757838","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>Between 31 March 2016 and 31 August 2017, 290 men and 569 women left HM Revenue and Customs under exit schemes.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-13T16:26:55.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757838/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757838/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","Revenue and Customs: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people who left HM Revenue and Customs under exit schemes since 31 March 2016 were (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757839","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>We have no plans to require parents to routinely disclose information about redundancy payments or savings as they are not taken into account as income within the calculation, nor can arrears be deducted from a redundancy payment prior to it being deposited into a bank account. Child maintenance arrears can be enforced against both savings and redundancy payments which have been paid out to the non-resident parent.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T12:04:52.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757839/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757839/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to bring forward proposals to include redundancy payments and savings in the mandatory disclosure to the Child Maintenance Service in the event of loss of employment by the paying parent.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757840","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of complaints about Personal Independence Payments is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Tier One complaints - A total of 6292 complaints were cleared, of which 5995 received a response within 15 working days.</p><p> </p><p>Tier Two complaints - A total of 170 complaints were cleared, of which 116 received a response within 15 working days.</p><p> </p><p>(Data provided for complaints closed within the 2016/2017 operational year)</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-13T10:37:45.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757840/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757840/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Personal Independence Payment: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) tier one and (b) tier two complaints relating to personal independence payments are responded to within 15 days.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757841","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>Where space is identified as being surplus to our business requirements it is surrendered to Telereal Trillium who are responsible for the cost of any subsequent commercial sub- letting.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-13T13:21:36.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757841/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757841/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The DWP target for clearing complaints for claims in relation to Personal Independence Payment is 95% within 15 days. Year-to-Date, from April 2017, the DWP is achieving 96%. A number of complaints are complex and require advice and guidance from, for example, legal colleagues, and such cases can take longer than 15 days. The DWP therefore considers that the teams handling complaints for Personal Independence Payment are sufficiently staffed.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T13:26:01.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757842/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether HM Revenue and Customs has sufficient staff to handle each and every complaint relating to personal independence payments within 15 days.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757843","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State has regular discussions with Cabinet colleagues including the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is developing a range of means of communications for ensuring people know their State Pension age. The ‘Check your State Pension’ service currently provides everyone with personal information on their forecast amount and when they will reach State Pension age. This service is already part of the online Personal Tax Account service.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T16:51:22.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757843/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757843/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on including a person's estimated retirement date on annual tax summaries.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757844","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department is currently in the process of enhancing the e-procurement system (Bravo) to enable such detailed reporting. At this time the information is not available without a major resource impact.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-13T13:47:44.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757844/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757844/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757845","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government published its assessment of the impacts of the change to the work-related activity component on 20 July 2015. <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006B.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006B.pdf</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T13:28:18.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757845/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757845/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of employment and support allowance payment levels; and if he will undertake a review of the adequacy of the financial support provided for people who are in the employment and support allowance work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757846","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-20","<p>Sanctions are only used in a minority of cases. For Employment and Support Allowance claimants the proportion of those sanctioned each month on average is 0.6% (based on the last year).</p><p> </p><p>ESA claimants are able to apply for hardship payments from the first day of a sanction. If the application is successful they will receive the payment from day 1 of the sanction.</p><p> </p><p>To keep the sanctions system clear, fair and effective in promoting positive behaviours, we keep the operation of the conditionality and sanction policies and processes under continuous review. Where we identify an issue, we act to put it right.</p><p>However, the use of conditionality and sanctions is only part of the story and cannot be seen in isolation to the work we are doing to continually improve the support we offer. The government continues to invest in trials, proofs of concept and feasibility studies to test ways to provide specialist support for people with health conditions, including those with mental health problems, and ensure that we are providing access to the most effective health and employment support when it is needed.</p><p> </p><p>Next steps for longer-term reform will be set out in the autumn in response to the <em>Improving Lives: The Work, Health and Disability Green Paper</em>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-20T11:03:54.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757846/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757846/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of sanctioning employment and support allowance claimants on assisting such people into work; and if he will undertake to review the use of sanctions on such claimants.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757847","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>On 10<sup>th</sup> July I met with the Trussell Trust to discuss their report.</p><p>Waiting days are an unpaid period at the start of a new claim to benefit, where a claimant has no entitlement to Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) or Employment and Support Allowance (ESA), but must continue to meet the relevant benefit conditions.</p><p>Not all claimants are required to serve waiting days. For example claimants who have a linking claim to another benefit within 13 weeks, JSA claimants under 18 and in severe hardship or ESA claimants who are terminally ill do not serve waiting days.</p><p>The fundamental principle behind the waiting days policy is that benefits are not intended to provide financial support for very brief periods, for example when someone is between jobs or during short periods of sickness.</p><p>The application of waiting days at the outset of a new claim means that more support can be targeted at initiatives to help move people off benefits and into work, for example, measures to improve the literacy and numeracy skills of claimants and provide more resources to support lone parents to return to employment.</p><p>JSA and ESA claimants are made aware that waiting days may apply when they make their new claim. This ensures that anyone suffering hardship can seek assistance as early as possible. Anyone who makes a new claim can apply for a Short Term Benefit Advance (STBA).</p><p>STBAs provide an advance of up to 60 per cent of the value of the first full benefit payment and are repaid through deductions from subsequent benefit payments. STBAs can provide a way to smooth the impact of extending waiting days across a longer period. The offer of a STBA is subject to checks to make sure that the claimant can afford the repayments.</p><p>There are similar arrangements for other out of work benefits where waiting days apply.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-13T14:54:58.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757847/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757847/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the implications for his policies on waiting times for (a) employment and support allowance, (b) jobseeker's allowance and (c) other out-of-work benefits are of the findings of the report, Financial insecurity, food insecurity and disability, published by the Trussell Trust in June 2017.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","8678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757848","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The leases for the buildings in question are included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and are therefore not held by DWP, all vacant space not required is surrendered back to Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>We have co-locations where other local government organisations that work closely with the Department share our space and occupy under a licence, these are few and far between and no central records are kept. The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T14:34:54.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757848/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757848/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757849","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>We have responded to a range of recommendations from five Independent Reviews.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we have consulted through the Work and Health Green Paper how we might improve the assessment process, and how we can use information more effectively to support this group in the future.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-11T12:47:28.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757849/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757849/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the work capability assessment in supporting disabled people into work; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","8607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757850","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>In the Improving Lives Green Paper we consulted on how Statutory Sick Pay could be reformed to encourage supportive conversations between the employer and employee and make it easier for people to make a phased return to work. We are now considering the full range of consultation responses and next steps on Statutory Sick Pay.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome Matthew Taylor’s ‘Good Work - Modern Working Practices’ and his detailed consideration of statutory sick pay. We are considering his recommendations in detail and will respond in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-11T12:50:16.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757850/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757850/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Statutory Sick Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to reform statutory sick pay as part of his Department's work to support more disabled people into employment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","8608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757851","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>General practitioners (GPs) are independent contractors who hold contracts with NHS England to provide primary medical services for the National Health Service. Under the terms of their contract, GPs are required to provide certain medical reports or complete certain forms free of charge to their registered patients. These certificates are those for which a medical report is required by other legislation for example, the Social Security Administration Act, and which are required for the purposes of ensuring public funds are allocated correctly.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement to provide these reports free of charge to patients remains, regardless of the way the practice is managed.</p><p> </p><p>Outside of contractual requirements, GPs also provide a variety of other services which successive governments have regarded as private matters between the patient and the GP providing these services. In such cases, decisions on whether to charge a fee and the level of the fee charged are at the GP’s discretion.</p><p> </p><p>The British Medical Association produces guidance on appropriate fee levels depending on workload. However, it is for individual GPs to decide whether to charge their patients and, if so, the level of any fee.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","9163","2017-09-11T14:22:40.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757851/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757851/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-05","Social Security Benefits: Medical Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department (a) has issued any guidance and (b) has imposed a requirement for private medical companies running GP surgeries to provide supporting letters for benefit claimants on request.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757852","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>HM Government has made significant progress on reducing the number of workless households. In April-June 2010 there were 3.95 million workless households. In April-June 2017 there were 3.0 million workless households, which is the lowest on record.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-13T15:08:09.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757852/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757852/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many workless households there were in (a) 2010 and (b) the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757853","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to supporting people with disabilities and long term health conditions to enter, remain in, and return to work, to deliver the health benefits that good work brings.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 below shows the estimated number of people in work with a disability or long-term health condition for quarter 2 of each year from 2010 to 2017. Due to a change in the definition of disability in 2013, estimates before and after this date should not be compared.</p><p> </p><p>From 2010-2012 the number of people in work with a disability increased by 23,000, from 3.244 million to 3.266 million. The number of people in work with a long term health condition decreased by 31,000 from 7.273 million to 7.243 million.</p><p> </p><p>From 2013-2017 the number of people in work with a disability increased by 596,000 from 2.897 million to 3.492 million. The number of people in work with a long term health condition increased by 595,000 from 6.847 million to 7.442 million.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Number of people in work with a disability or long-term health condition for quarter 2 of each year from 2010 to 2017, UK</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of people with a disability in work (thousands)</p></td><td><p>Number of people with a long-term health condition in work (thousands)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2010</p></td><td><p>3,244</p></td><td><p>7,273</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2011</p></td><td><p>3,275</p></td><td><p>7,368</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2012</p></td><td><p>3,266</p></td><td><p>7,243</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2013</p></td><td><p>2,897</p></td><td><p>6,847</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2014</p></td><td><p>3,026</p></td><td><p>6,794</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2015</p></td><td><p>3,257</p></td><td><p>7,077</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2016</p></td><td><p>3,388</p></td><td><p>7,239</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Q2 2017</p></td><td><p>3,492</p></td><td><p>7,442</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Labour Force Survey, available at: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08</a>.</p><p> </p><p>But we know that there is much more that needs to be done, so that everyone who can work is given the right support and opportunities to do so. That is why we published Improving Lives; the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper, which set out the action we plan to take to achieve this and start a far-reaching, national debate on what more we can do to ensure everyone is supported to reach their full potential. The Government is currently carefully considering next steps.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T13:44:41.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757853/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757853/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Health: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many more people with a disability or long-term health condition are in work compared with 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","8959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757854","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The DWP claimant satisfaction and experience survey currently only covers Universal Credit Live Service claimants. The available figures cover the financial year 2015/16.</p><p>We continue to monitor and evaluate the delivery of Universal Credit. To date there have been a number of published reports where claimants responded to surveys. As Universal Credit is rolled out to new areas of the country we will continue to involve claimants in the overall evaluation.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7847 ; 8979","2017-09-11T12:18:18.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757854/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757854/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claimants on full service universal credit were satisfied with the service received in the most recent period for which figures are available; and what that satisfaction rate was in (a) live and (b) full service areas.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","8924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757855","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>We are intending to publish further data on payment timeliness in due course, but our latest internal data nationally, suggests around 80% of cases are paid in full at the end of the first assessment period.</p><p> </p><p>For the remaining cases we estimate around a third have not signed up to their claimant commitment so cannot be paid until they have. The other two thirds have an outstanding verification issue, such as providing bank statements, evidence of childcare costs, or proof of rent. Many of these claimants receive a part-payment where elements of the claim have been verified.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7328 ; 7329 ; 7431 ; 9191","2017-09-11T12:21:29.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757855/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757855/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of claimants on full service universal credit have not been paid in full within six weeks in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","8923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757856","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>As internet access can be an issue for some claimants, including those in rural areas, all jobcentres across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available, including 6000 additional computers installed to support the introduction of Universal Credit. This provides access to digital channels in every Jobcentre for claimants to use when they do not have access at home. A telephone helpline and face to face support are also available for claimants to make and manage a Universal Credit claim.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-13T15:12:11.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757856/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757856/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Universal Credit: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to support new claimants of universal credit in rural areas with a lack of access to online facilities.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","8917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757857","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The DWP claimant satisfaction and experience survey currently only covers Universal Credit Live Service claimants. The available figures cover the financial year 2015/16.</p><p>We continue to monitor and evaluate the delivery of Universal Credit. To date there have been a number of published reports where claimants responded to surveys. As Universal Credit is rolled out to new areas of the country we will continue to involve claimants in the overall evaluation.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7847 ; 8924","2017-09-11T12:18:18.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757857/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757857/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Minister for Employment's oral contribution of 27 June 2017, Official Report, column 570, on universal credit customers' satisfaction, whether the universal credit claimants referred to were on (a) live and (b) full service; and over what period of time those claimants reported their satisfaction.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","8979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757858","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-13","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State has written to the Chief Executive of Ofgem asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will consider further action in the light of Ofgem’s proposals and remains prepared to legislate if necessary.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-13T14:11:19.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757858/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757858/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to introduce an energy price cap.","false","Biography information for Liz Twist","Blaydon","Liz Twist","8916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757859","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government is considering the findings of the independent Hendry Review before deciding, in light of the relevant factors, its position on the proposed Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon project.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-13T14:16:09.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757859/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757859/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757859/answer/previousversion/9855","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will publish a timetable for the announcement of its decision on the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","8920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757860","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The potential social and economic benefits of connected and autonomous vehicle technology are significant, and securing these benefits along with the tremendous industrial opportunities associated with developing and producing them is central to the Government’s strategy.</p><p>The Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles has commissioned research to better understand the industrial opportunity.</p><p>Published on the 7<sup>th</sup> September 2017, the research estimates that the market for connected and autonomous vehicles is estimated to be worth £28bn in the UK in 2035.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-11T16:42:42.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757860/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757860/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the financial benefit to the public purse of the introduction of autonomous vehicles.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","8940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757861","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has said it will bring forward reforms to the approach to the ownership and control of critical infrastructure to ensure that the full implications of foreign ownership are scrutinised for the purposes of national security. The Government will publish the outcome of this review in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T16:22:16.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757861/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757861/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Takeovers: Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of a public interest test for takeovers of major UK companies supporting the UK's science base.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","8930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757862","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>The Government will consider this issue in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going work to review building safety.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-25T11:30:45.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757862/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757862/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Insulation: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to strengthen product safety and market surveillance of cladding as a result of the Grenfell Tower disaster.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","8621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757863","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK has a strong history of protecting consumer rights, and this will continue after we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>UK consumer protections that are based on EU law will be retained through the EU Withdrawal Bill. This means that when buying from traders based in the UK British consumers will be able to rely on the same rights they have now.</p><p> </p><p>The way consumer protections apply internationally in future (for example when purchasing goods online from an EU trader) is a matter for negotiations. We are carefully considering how best to cooperate on these issues with our EU partners after our exit.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T12:44:55.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757863/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757863/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Consumers: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to protect and strengthen  consumer rights when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","8623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757864","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>National Trading Standards receive £13.24 million per year from BEIS to prioritise and coordinate national and cross-local authority boundary enforcement in England and Wales, including action to stop the sale of counterfeit electrical goods.</p><p> </p><p>National Trading Standards ‘Operation Jasper’ resulted in the seizure of over £1m in counterfeit goods including luxury brands, dangerous electrical equipment and unsafe cosmetic products in 2016. This included an operation by Swansea Trading Standards to target commercial vehicles carrying counterfeit goods.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T15:41:26.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757864/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757864/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Trading Standards: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much funding his Department has allocated to Welsh trading standards offices to tackle counterfeit electrical goods being imported into Wales.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","8622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757865","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>There is good progress being made on a number of early sector deals, including the life sciences sector, which published a report to Government last week and intent to have reached agreement on six sector deals for the white paper later this year. The early sector deals will serve as an example of how Government can work with sectors of the economy to enhance their earning power. We are prepared to work with any sector which can organise strong leadership to address shared challenges and opportunities to grow the earning potential and engagement in their sector.</p><p> </p><p>.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-10T14:39:07.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757865/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757865/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress is being made on creating sector deals as part of the industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Ross Thomson","Aberdeen South","Ross Thomson","8628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757866","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department is working to ensure the domestic private rented property minimum energy efficiency regulations are implemented as effectively as possible. We expect to provide further details shortly, including through publishing guidance on implementing the regulations.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-14T15:59:17.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757866/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757866/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Energy: Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to amend minimum energy standards for rented homes.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","8629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757867","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-21","<p>The Government has a duty under section 165 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to carry out a review of the minimum energy performance requirements for new homes in the Building Regulations. As set out in the Housing White Paper - <em>Fixing our broken housing market – </em>work has started on the review and we will consult on improving the requirements on new homes if evidence suggests that there are opportunities to do so without making homes less affordable for those who want to buy their own home.</p><p>This will be in the context of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going building safety work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-21T11:04:48.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757867/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757867/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment his Department has made of progress towards ensuring that all new homes are ultra-low emission from 2020.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","8630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757868","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Energy Company Obligation, worth £640m per year to 2022, has helped improve the energy efficiency of over 1.6 million homes since 2013. We are also introducing new regulations that will require that all new private rental tenancies from April 2018 must meet a minimum energy efficiency of EPC Band E.</p><p>Furthermore, the domestic RHI offers support for a range of technologies and fuel uses such as solid biomass, heat pumps, and solar thermal and, at the end of July 2017, 57,203 installations had been accredited.</p><p>Our Clean Growth Strategy will set out further proposals for reducing carbon emissions.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-12T16:11:14.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757868/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757868/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Carbon Emissions: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to improve the carbon efficiency of homes.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","8631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757869","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government is committed to seeing greater diversity on company boards. My department has supported and promoted various initiatives to promote gender diversity on boards and across the public sector. These include:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>the Lord Davies Review, which established a business-led voluntary approach and has seen the proportion of women on FTSE 350 boards increase from 9.5% in 2011 to 24.4% in September 2017;</p></li><li><p>the subsequent Hampton-Alexander Review, which has set a target of 33% women on FTSE 350 boards by 2020;</p></li><li><p>in conjunction with UK Government Investments, actively supporting the Future Boards Scheme, a business-led initiative to help talented, senior women get board-level development opportunities and gain the experience they need to successfully apply for board positions;</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>a new Business Diversity and Inclusion Group to improve the coordination of diversity initiatives and provide a clear and coherent message on what is expected of the business community; as well as</p></li><li><p>work promoting boardroom diversity in the public and third sectors.</p><p> </p></li></ul><p>All of these various initiatives will contribute to our continued efforts to ensure gender-balanced representation and that boardrooms reflect their workforces and wider society.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T12:58:10.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757869/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757869/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Directors: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to increase the representation of women on company boards.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757870","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>We do not keep records of the duration of procurement for those managed directly by the department. For those procurements managed by our shared service provider UKSBS, the number of procurements at those durations, undertaken by BEIS since April 2015 is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Duration</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Volume</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(a) 3 months</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) 6 months</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) 1 year</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(d) 2 years</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-12T14:58:58.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757870/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757870/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757871","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy estates management records system was created in 2012.</p><p>There is no record of letting fees being paid to agents since that date.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-12T15:01:43.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757871/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757871/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757872","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy estates management records system was created in 2012. Rental income from its estate since then is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Rental Income</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>£9,975,567.28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>£11,992,752.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>£20,873,669.59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>£16,889,083.94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>£22,404,118.73</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-12T14:59:52.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757872/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757872/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757873","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>BEIS Ministers and officials regularly meet energy supply companies to discuss a wide range of issues. We are working with Ofgem to make switching supplier quicker and easier for consumers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T13:22:26.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757873/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757873/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent meetings he has had with the Big Six energy companies; and what measures his Department plans to being forward to ensure the energy market is a competitive marketplace.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757874","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has written to the Chief Executive of Ofgem asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will consider Ofgem’s proposals and their potential impact on vulnerable consumers, in deciding on how to proceed.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T16:40:37.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757874/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757874/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to page 78 of the publication entitled Queen's Speech 2017: background briefing notes, if his Department will estimate the number of vulnerable energy customers on the poorest value tariffs who will be covered by extending energy price protection; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757875","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Peaceful protest is a vital part of a democratic society. People must be free to gather together and to demonstrate their views, provided that they do so within the law.</p><p> </p><p>But protestors' rights must be balanced with the rights of others to go about their business without fear of intimidation or serious disruption to the community. Rights to peaceful protest do not extend to violent or threatening behaviour and the police have powers to deal with any such acts.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS and the Home Office have regular discussions across a wide range of topics of mutual interest, including protest activity related to fracking.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-11T12:55:52.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757875/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757875/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Fracking: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department has had with the Home Office on preventing intimidation of people legally involved in fracking.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","8857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757876","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>I made an oral statement to the House on 11 July 2017 to announce the publication of the Matthew Taylor Review of Modern Working Practices.</p><p> </p><p>The Review looked at ways to ensure that the regulatory framework surrounding employment, and the support Government provides to businesses and workers, was keeping pace with changes in the labour market and the economy.</p><p> </p><p>The report is comprehensive and detailed and will require detailed, careful thought and further consultation. It is important that we take action where we need to.</p><p> </p><p>This Government will give the report the careful consideration it deserves and will respond in full later this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T12:53:56.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757876/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757876/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment the Government has made of whether all employees should have rights to parental leave, holiday pay, full sick pay and guaranteed hours.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757877","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-13","<p>The RTFO Unit in the Department for Transport operates the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) which supports the market for sustainable biofuel by means of a certificate trading scheme. The Department is also supporting the commercialisation of advanced biofuels by grant funding through the Advanced Biofuel Demonstration Competition. Departmental funding includes budgets for policy development, analysis and research into low carbon fuels, including (but not limited to) biofuels.</p><p> </p><p>The table below sets out readily identifiable expenditure for the last five full financial years.</p><p><strong>Public spending related to biofuels (and low carbon fuels)</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Low Carbon Fuels </strong> <strong>research programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>RTFO Unit </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Advanced Biofuel Demonstration Competition</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£63,000</p></td><td><p>£905,000</p></td><td><p>£6,548,000</p></td><td><p><strong>£7,516,000 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£56,000</p></td><td><p>£694,000</p></td><td><p>£973,000</p></td><td><p><strong>£1,723,000 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£106,000</p></td><td><p>£701,000</p></td><td><p>£106,000</p></td><td><p><strong>£913,000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£131,000</p></td><td><p>£706,000</p></td><td><p>£83,000</p></td><td><p><strong>£920,000 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£6,000</p></td><td><p>£584,000</p></td><td><p>nil</p></td><td><p><strong>£590,000 </strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-13T11:07:26.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757877/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757877/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-05","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much public funding has been provided related to biofuels in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757878","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-13","<p>The <em>Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and Wales) Regulations 2015</em> require all landlords of domestic privately rented property in England and Wales to ensure that, from 1 April 2018, their properties reach at least an energy performance rating of E before granting a tenancy to new or existing tenants, unless a prescribed exemption applies.</p><p>Tenants would benefit from improved homes in the form of reduced energy bills. Data derived from the 2014 English Housing Survey shows that the average annual cost of heating an E rated home in the private rental sector to an adequate level is £510 cheaper than for an F rated private rented sector home, and £990 cheaper than for a G rated property. There would also be wider health and wellbeing benefits for tenants associated with increased comfort from warmer homes.</p><p>The published impact assessment for the regulations estimated that effective implementation of the domestic provisions will save 1.8 million tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent between 2013 and 2065.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-13T15:56:27.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757878/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757878/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Energy: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment the Government has made of the benefits (a) for tenants and (b) in terms of carbon emissions of raising the minimum energy efficiency standards for privately rented homes.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757879","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>As set out in the Housing White Paper - <em>Fixing our broken housing market – </em>we have started work on a review of the cost effectiveness of current minimum energy efficiency standards in the Building Regulations for new homes. We will consult on improving the requirements on new homes if evidence suggests that there are opportunities to do so without making homes less affordable for those who want to buy their own home. The review will also consider the energy efficiency requirements for works to existing properties covered by the Building Regulations, such as home extensions.</p><p>The forthcoming <em>Clean Growth Plan </em>will also set out our ambitions for improving the energy efficiency of existing properties more widely.</p><p>All of this work will be in context of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going building safety work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-25T11:28:58.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757879/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757879/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-05","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what targets the Government has for improving the energy efficiency of (a) new build homes and (b) existing properties.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","8879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757880","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has not made a specific assessment of the effect of artificial intelligence on consumer mis-selling.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T10:17:56.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757880/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757880/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","Sales: Misrepresentation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of artificial intelligence on consumer mis-selling.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757881","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Heat Network (Metering and Billing) Regulations 2014 aims to bring benefits to heat network consumers by increasing the number of metered properties and providing more transparent metering and billing information. Under the regulations, heat suppliers are required to install meters and base bills on actual consumption, where it is cost effective and technically feasible to do so, and for all consumers they must clearly set out how the bill was calculated. Heat network customers are also covered by general consumer protection and competition law.</p><p>We welcome the work of the heat network industry to bring in elements of self-regulation, by establishing the ‘Heat Trust’, an independent customer protection scheme that draws upon and seeks to set equivalent terms of service as offered to gas and electric customers. The industry has also developed a voluntary Code of Practice, which establishes minimum standards for the design, installation and operation of heat networks.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-13T12:09:19.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757881/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757881/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757881/answer/previousversion/9856","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","District Heating: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what regulations apply to district heating schemes to protect consumers.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","8815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757882","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>This is a commercial matter for the parties concerned.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T13:35:12.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757882/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757882/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-05","AVEVA: Schneider Electric","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the UK economy of the proposed takeover of Aveva by Schneider Electric.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","8816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757883","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for International Trade provides support to businesses in all four nations of the Union, through programmes like the Overseas Market Information Service and via the High Value Campaigns. In addition, our digital platform GREAT.GOV.UK provides access to millions of pounds’ worth of business opportunities; and provides a searchable export directory to match businesses.</p><p> </p><p>UK Export Finance (UKEF) offers finance and credit insurance to Scottish businesses to ensure no viable export fails. UKEF has Export Finance Managers based in Scotland to help businesses get paid for their overseas sales.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-09-13T06:42:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757883/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757883/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Exports: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what programmes his Department provides to small and medium-sized businesses in Scotland to support the expansion of export sales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757884","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has regular discussions with the Nigerian Government on trade. We work to improve the business environment and increase business confidence, to promote long-term growth and a diversified economy. The Prime Minister's Trade Envoy to Nigeria visits regularly as part of HMG's coordinated activity to promote our trade and prosperity priorities. My Rt hon Friends the Foreign Secretary and Secretary of State for International Development emphasised the UK’s commitment to strengthen bilateral trade ties further during their recent visit to Nigeria. DIT is organising infrastructure and agribusiness trade missions to the UK in October to highlight opportunities in these sectors.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-09-13T17:05:40.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757884/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757884/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Trade Agreements: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how the Government plans to strengthen and promote its trade and investment relationship with Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","8874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757885","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-13","<p>Recently, I witnessed the transformative work DFID is doing in Nigeria, with the Government and the private sector, to build a better future for the largest youth population in Africa. DFID is providing critical healthcare in the early stages of life, educating over 1 million children, and supporting livelihoods, jobs and investment across the country, and has raised the incomes of 1.38 million Nigerians since 2015.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-13T11:02:12.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757885/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757885/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-05","Young People: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what measures the Government is putting in place with the Nigerian Government to support the economic and developmental potential of Nigeria's youth population.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","8872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757886","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for International Trade has paid no letting fees since it was created in July 2016.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-13T16:56:36.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757886/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757886/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Department for International Trade: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757887","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) does not publish export data on a constituency or a country level. Nevertheless, DIT can identify that Scottish companies have used DIT export support programmes including the Tradeshow Access Programme, services accessed through the great.gov.uk digital platform, activities in the High Value Campaigns and commissioned Overseas Market Information Services. Companies such as Alexander Dennis have also utilised UK Export Finance support such as their recent contract to supply buses to Mexico.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-09-13T06:48:39.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757887/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757887/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Exports: Stirling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many businesses in Stirling constituency are engaged with his Department in promoting their export sales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","8909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757888","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for International Trade has not sub-let any of its estate since it was created in July 2016 and therefore has received no income from sub-lets.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-12T14:10:31.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757888/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757888/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Department for International Trade: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757889","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-13","<p>In line with Government Policy for best practice in public sector procurement, the Department for International Trade Commercial Function seeks to undertake procurements as efficiently as possible, to minimise resources used both on Government and supplier side.</p><p> </p><p>Since the creation of the Department for International Trade in June 2016, the Commercial Function has logged 23 procurements with values above the £106,047 threshold, for advertising in the Official Journal of the European Union. Of these: two have taken over three months to procure, one has taken over six months to procure and one has taken over one year to procure. The duration of the procurement is measured from issuing the invitation to tender to awarding the contract.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-13T16:54:41.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757889/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757889/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-05","Department for International Trade: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757890","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK’s relationship with the EU's agencies upon exit will be evaluated in light of delivering the twelve objectives outlined by the Prime Minister to achieve a deep and special partnership between the UK and the EU. The UK’s future relationship with the EU's decentralised bodies after leaving the EU is a matter for the negotiations.</p><p>Prior to any decisions on establishing new agencies, the Government will, however, always look to minimise disruption and costs, which will include considering alternative options.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-11T17:14:47.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757890/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757890/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-09-05","Government Departments: Arms Length Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many new arm's-length bodies across the whole of government he expects will need to be created when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757891","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has not undertaken a procurement which has taken more than three months, six months or one year. Two years is out of scope as this would predate the establishment of the Department.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-13T15:35:34.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757891/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757891/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-05","Department for Exiting the European Union: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many procurements undertaken by his Department have taken more than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757892","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-28","<p>Meetings of the Joint Ministerial Committee and its sub-committees have taken place on the following dates since June 2016:</p><p>(a) JMC(EU Negotiations) met 9 November 2016, 7 December 2016, 19 January 2017 and 8 February 2017. We anticipate the next meeting of JMC(EN) will take place in the autumn. The UK’s exit from the EU was also discussed at sessions of JMC (Plenary) on 24 October 2016 and 30 January 2017.</p><p>(b) JMC(EU Negotiations) Officials meetings took place on 16 September 2016, 25 October 2016, 7 November 2016, 17 November 2016, 28 November 2016, 12 December 2016 and 21 December 2016 and on 10 January 2017, 17 January 2017, 31 January 2017, 6 February 2017 and 15 February 2017. Meetings of JMC Officials took place on 27 September 2016, 10 October 2016, 17 October 2016, 21 October 2016 and 25 November 2016 and on 6 January 2017 and 23 January 2017. The next meeting of JMC Officials is scheduled for 8 September 2017.</p><p>JMC(Europe) and JMC (Europe) Officials have continued to meet during this period to discuss business as usual.</p><p>In addition, officials from all administrations meet regularly in a variety of other formats.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-09-28T11:23:59.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757892/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757892/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-05","Joint Ministerial Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and which meetings of the Joint Ministerial Committee and its sub-committees at both (a) Ministerial and (b) official level have been convened to discuss the UK leaving the EU in which the Welsh Government has been involved since the referendum on the UK leaving the EU, in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","8707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757893","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union occupies properties managed by other government departments. It has not received any income from sub-letting property.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T11:37:35.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757893/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757893/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-09-05","Department for Exiting the European Union: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has received from sub-lets on its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757894","Department for Exiting the European Union","true","2017-09-11","<p>As part of our commitment to hear from every sector and region in the UK, Ministers and officials in the Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) and across government, have spoken to a range of civil society organisations, including consumer groups. Ministers and officials from DExEU <ins class="ministerial">and the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy</ins> have met organisations including Which?, Money Saving Expert, the British Retail Consortium and Citizens Advice, and as part of our programme of cross-Whitehall engagement, we have plans to host a roundtable with consumer groups. We will draw on their expertise, understand their perspectives and work with them to test and validate positions as we prepare to leave the European Union.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-11T13:49:06.26Z","2017-10-12T17:33:19.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757894/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757894/answer","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757894/answer/previousversion/9477","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-05","Consumers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many times he has (a) invited and (b) met with consumer groups to discuss negotiations on the UK leaving the EU and their implications for consumers in the UK.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","8695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757895","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>On the financial settlement, we have acknowledged that the UK has obligations to the EU and the EU to the UK, that will survive the UK’s withdrawal - which need to be resolved. We will continue discussions on how we determine a fair settlement of the UK’s rights and obligations as a departing member state, in accordance with the law and in the spirit of the UK’s continuing partnership with the EU.</p><p>In July the Commission set out the European Union position. We have a duty to our taxpayers to interrogate that position rigorously.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T16:32:21.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757895/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757895/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-05","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate has been made of the amount his Department plans to pay for the UK to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757896","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government is negotiating our exit from the European Union. Defra is working with the Department for Exiting the European Union to look at future arrangements including for the UK’s system for the management of agri-food imports and exports.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-11T16:22:57.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757896/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757896/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-05","Agricultural Products: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether it is the Government's policy to seek to remain part of the TRACES online management tool after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","8670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757897","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union occupies properties managed by other government departments. It has not paid any letting fees.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T11:39:57.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757897/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757897/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-05","Department for Exiting the European Union: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has paid in letting fees for its estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757898","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The arrangements for withdrawal from the EU, including financial matters, will be a matter for the withdrawal agreement as part of the Article 50 process.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T11:39:11.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757898/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/757898/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-05","European Union: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the (a) proportion and (b) total amount of EU assets that the UK will be entitled to on the day that the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","8986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759062","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Higher Education sector is taking this issue very seriously. The Department has had a very positive and comprehensive response from all of the 238 HEFCE-funded providers and designated Alternative Providers. All providers have been tested where necessary. Where issues have been identified providers have been quick to respond to protect the safety of students. Officials will continue to work with those in the Department for Communities and Local Government reviewing private student accommodation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-11T16:43:54.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759062/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759062/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Students: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of fire safety standards in university halls of residence.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","900762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759063","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>The student finance system is financially sustainable and has enabled record numbers of students from disadvantaged backgrounds to benefit from higher education.</p><p> </p><p>Latest data show that 18 year olds applied at record rates in 2017, and their application rates have increased for five years in a row. This is also true for the most disadvantaged 18 year olds.</p><p> </p><p>Non-continuation rates for UK students at English Higher Education Institutions are lower than in 2009/10, including for young, mature, disadvantaged and BME students.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-11T16:26:38.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759063/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759063/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of student loan debt on the level of university applications and drop-out rates.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","900759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759064","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>Women have accounted for the majority of apprenticeship starts in recent years - 52.8 per cent in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>But we know there are gender representation disparities in some sectors. We are addressing this proactively through our Diversity Champions Network, by taking part in the 2018 Year of Engineering campaign and other Government actions.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","900756","2017-09-11T15:56:51.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759064/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759064/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Apprentices: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that women can access high-quality apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Andrew Lewer","Northampton South","Andrew Lewer","900757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759065","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>Women have accounted for the majority of apprenticeship starts in recent years - 52.8 per cent in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>But we know there are gender representation disparities in some sectors. We are addressing this proactively through our Diversity Champions Network, by taking part in the 2018 Year of Engineering campaign and other Government actions.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","900757","2017-09-11T15:56:51.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759065/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759065/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Apprentices: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that women can access high-quality apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","900756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759066","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>The 2016 School Workforce Census shows teacher retention rates have remained stable for teachers over the first five years of their careers. We recognised the problem of unnecessary workload when we launched the Workload Challenge in 2014. Our responses to this and the 2016 Teacher Workload Survey set out comprehensive programmes of action to be taken. We continue our extensive work with the profession, teaching unions and Ofsted to support the retention of teachers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-11T15:49:49.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759066/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759066/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-05","Teachers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to improve the retention of teachers.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","900755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759922","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government has been clear that it is a priority to maintain the Common Travel Area. Border Force actively monitors its work to ensure sufficient resources are in place to meet demand and will continue to do so throughout negotiations and as the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-13T16:40:10.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759922/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759922/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-05","Cross Border Cooperation: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on changes to (a) the way in which the border with the Republic of Ireland will be policed for immigration purposes and (b) the resources allocated to the Border Force after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","900733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759923","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Universal Credit will make work pay. It will support people in Northern Ireland who are on a low income or out of work, helping to ensure that they are better off in work than on benefits.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-09-13T14:40:17.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759923/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759923/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-05","Universal Credit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of universal credit on family incomes in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","900734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759924","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The 2015 Fresh Start Agreement included a number of measures aimed at tackling paramilitary activity. While the Northern Ireland Civil Service continues to implement the Executive’s Paramilitary Action Plan, Executive ministers would be best placed to drive this work. This is another example of the importance of devolved government.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-13T16:38:37.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759924/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759924/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-05","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions he has had with political parties in Northern Ireland on the incidence of paramilitary activity.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","900736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759925","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The fundamentals of the Northern Ireland economy remain strong, with growth last year at 1.6%.</p><p> </p><p>Economic activity is up, unemployment has fallen to levels not seen since before the Great Recession of 2008, and 43,000 more people are in work compared to 2010.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-09-13T14:29:16.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759925/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759925/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-05","Economic Situation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent assessment he has made of the performance of the Northern Ireland economy.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","900735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755523","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>Under the Constitutional Reform Act 2005 the responsibility for judicial training rests with the Lord Chief Justice and is exercised through the Judicial College. Since 2002, all judges who hear cases involving serious sexual offences have to be first authorised and are required to attend the specialist training provided by the Judicial College before hearing such cases. Listing, which is a judicial function, ensures that cases are allocated to those who are authorised and trained.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-12T19:13:17.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755523/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755523/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Judges: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to ensure that all judges who hear rape cases have attended and completed a relevant course accredited by the Judicial College.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","6906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755524","Attorney General","false","2017-09-07","<p>I regularly meet ministerial colleagues to discuss important issues of common interest, including on matters of international criminal law. By longstanding convention, the fact that the Law Officers have or have not given advice to Cabinet on a particular issue, and the content of their advice, is not disclosed outside Government.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-07T14:14:51.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755524/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755524/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Crime of aggression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the ratification of crimes of aggression as defined by the International Criminal Court into domestic law.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","7380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755525","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>One of the four principal objectives of the new National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) is to respond to cyber security incidents to reduce the harm they cause to the UK. Since its formation, the NCSC has managed approximately 60 serious incidents affecting government and industry each month. The total number of cyber incidents affecting central government departments, including DDoS attacks and ransomware infections, is not centrally recorded.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7046","2017-09-12T14:44:39.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755525/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755525/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many distributed denial of service cyber attacks on central Government Departments have occurred in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755526","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>As outlined in our manifesto, the Government is committed to legislating to scrap the 15-year rule and will do so in time for the next scheduled parliamentary general election in 2022.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-07T15:15:50.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755526/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755526/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Voting Rights: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to introduce legislation to provide for votes for life for UK citizens living abroad.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755527","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>As outlined in our manifesto, the Government is committed to legislating to scrap the 15-year rule and will do so in time for the next scheduled parliamentary general election in 2022.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-07T15:15:30.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755527/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755527/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Voting Rights: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to extend overseas voting rights for life.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","7206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755528","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Services under the Robotic Process Automation (RPA) Partnership contract began on 4 September 2017 and there is not currently enough analysis on which to base an estimate of potential savings or improvements to public services. The initial focus of the contract is to develop a Centre of Excellence that promotes RPA across government and helps Departments identify suitable opportunities for automation. The initial services are being provided at the supplier's cost and we will only pay for services where we agree terms for full development and deployment of RPA applications into Departments.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T15:22:17.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755528/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755528/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Automation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the savings to the public purse as a result of the robotic process automation campaign put out to tender by his Department; and what the evidential basis was for that estimate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755529","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and would incur disproportionate costs to determine.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:10:34.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755529/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755529/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to data published by the Office for National Statistics in July 2017, how many of the 555 additional staff employed in digital, data and technology roles in the Civil Service since March 2016 were recruited (a) internally and (b) externally.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7226"
