"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755536","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>As outlined in our manifesto, the Government is committed to legislating to scrap the 15-year rule and will do so in time for the next scheduled parliamentary general election in 2022.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-07T15:15:13.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755536/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755536/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Voting Rights: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government has plans to introduce legislative proposals to allow Britons living abroad for longer than 15 years to vote in UK elections; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","6973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755537","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The last meeting of the GDS Advisory Board was in January 2017. Due to an administrative oversight, the minutes for this meeting had not previously been published. This has now been rectified and the minutes are available on gov.uk.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-07T14:15:45.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755537/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755537/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Digital Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the GDS Advisory Board minutes for the first and second quarters of 2017 have not been published.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","6989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755538","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Civil Service is committed to becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK and as such works hard to understand the impact of recruitment on the diversity of its workforce.</p><p>Anonymised recruitment, less formally referred to as ‘name blind’ recruitment, is just one of these initiatives and is intended to assure candidates that people are assessed on the basis of the evidence that they present.</p><p>There is a significant focus on diversity and this policy is important as part of a wider suite of evidence based initiatives that when implemented together are more likely to have a positive impact on the diversity of the Civil Service.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:05:48.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755538/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755538/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of what changes have resulted in the outcomes of Civil Service recruitment since the introduction of name-blind and school-blind recruitment.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755539","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since the Civil Service Apprenticeship Strategy was introduced in 2015, the current number of Civil Service Apprenticeship starts is confirmed at 7,709 (last collected on 31st March 2017). The Civil Service does not yet have data on completed apprenticeships but began recording this information in April 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Civil Service is on track to achieve its target of 30,000 apprenticeship starts by 2020 as laid out in the Apprenticeship Strategy.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:19:29.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755539/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755539/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil service apprenticeships have been (a) awarded and (b) completed in each year since they were introduced.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755540","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Civil Service Workforce Plan (2016) sets out the importance of movement in and out of the Civil Service, in order to exchange skills and expertise and enable the Civil Service to respond to changing priorities and deliver Government commitments. The Civil Service Talent Board oversees the approach to secondments and regularly reviews this. It last discussed it in May 2017, and considered how to build on the work of the High Potential Secondments Programme and how to ensure we are using secondments to meet capability needs, particularly in relation to the EU exit.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T10:12:28.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755540/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755540/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Civil Service secondment and interchange strategy was last updated.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755541","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Civil Service Executive Recruitment expert service was established in 2013 and<br>formally launched in 2014 to deliver a centralised recruitment function for senior roles<br>across the Civil Service. This approach ensures that departments are provided with expert<br>guidance on attracting and selecting a diverse range of quality candidates. The expert<br>service currently covers approximately 40% of all SCS recruitment and has facilitated the<br>recruitment of over 900 individuals since it was established.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T10:14:38.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755541/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755541/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Senior Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress has been made on centralising the senior recruitment function in the Civil Service as set out in the Civil Service Workforce Plan 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755542","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Departments are responsible for their own recruitment, with around 40% of Senior Civil Service vacancies through the centralised Executive Recruitment service. There is no central collection of recruitment information across government or the associated spend.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7044","2017-09-12T14:31:05.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755542/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755542/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Senior Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times executive search firms have been contracted for the purpose of recruitment into the Civil Service since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755543","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Departments are responsible for their own recruitment, with around 40% of Senior Civil Service vacancies through the centralised Executive Recruitment service. There is no central collection of recruitment information across government or the associated spend.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7043","2017-09-12T14:31:05.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755543/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755543/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Senior Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been spent on executive search firms contracted for the purpose of recruitment into the Civil Service since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755544","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Unfortunately, the department only holds information regarding advertised roles in the Civil Service from January 2011. The information below includes appointments advertised on Civil Service jobs, which includes adverts from 159 government departments and organisations, and appointments to the Civil Service Fast Stream and through the Fast Track apprenticeship scheme.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Departments are able to recruit through third party providers however, meaning that this response is not representational of all advertised roles for the Civil Service, only the ones that are advertised centrally. It is also worth noting that the Civil Service Fast Track Apprenticeship only started in 2013.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Cabinet Office will not be including information on appointments to the Senior Civil Service as this will be covered by a separate response to a different Parliamentary Question you have submitted.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The proportion of civil service roles that were advertised externally since January 2011 is as follows.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2011 – 25.9%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2012 – 35.4%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2013 – 30.6%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2014 – 31.6%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2015 – 46.4%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2016 – 53.7% - not including Fast Stream figures as these are being prepared for future publication</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:08:03.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755544/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755544/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of civil service roles were advertised externally for each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755545","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The CyberFirst programme covers a range of activities; a bursary scheme, girls only competition and development events for students aged between 11-17 years. For the CyberFirst bursary programme 2016/2017 the gender breakdown was 21% female, 79% male. The 2017/2018 campaign is still ongoing but of those candidates that have applied so far, 23% are female. 43% of attendees at 2017 CyberFirst development events were female.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:13:06.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755545/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755545/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the gender breakdown is of the young people who have completed the Government's CyberFirst programme.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755546","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) was established formally on 3 October 2016. At that time, the NCSC had a team of approximately 700 people. For reasons of National Security, we will not be providing further releases on staff numbers and recruitment.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:09:30.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755546/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755546/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","National Cyber Security Centre: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many members of staff are employed in the National Cyber-Security Centre.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755547","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>One of the four principal objectives of the new National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) is to respond to cyber security incidents to reduce the harm they cause to the UK. Since its formation, the NCSC has managed approximately 60 serious incidents affecting government and industry each month. The total number of cyber incidents affecting central government departments, including DDoS attacks and ransomware infections, is not centrally recorded.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7314","2017-09-12T14:44:39.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755547/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755547/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many ransomware cyber attacks on central Government departments there have been by year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755548","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) was established formally on 3 October 2016. At that time, the NCSC had a team of approximately 700 people. For reasons of National Security, we will not be providing further releases on staff numbers and recruitment.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7050","2017-09-12T10:09:30.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755548/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755548/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","National Cyber Security Centre: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff members of the National Cyber-Security Centre were recruited (a) from within and (b) externally to the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755549","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>£10 million out of the £155 million is available in this financial year to the Defence Innovation Fund, to support innovative procurement across Defence. The Fund is harnessing the best ideas from inside and outside of Defence through activities such as themed competitions and the Open Call for Innovation, delivered using the Defence and Security Accelerator, available at the following link:</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/organisations.defence-and-security-accelerator</p><p>The Government also allocated £10 million to establish a Cyber Innovation Fund. This supports the UK's national security requirements by providing innovative start-ups with financial and procurement support.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-09-12T13:56:41.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755549/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755549/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Cyber Innovation Fund and Defence Innovation Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much of the £165 million Defence and Cyber Innovation Fund has been allocated to support innovative procurement in defence and security; and to what use that money has been put.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755550","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>Since the launch of the Cyber Essentials scheme in June 2014 there has been an ongoing upward trend in the number of certificates awarded to organisations, with 7,907 certificates awarded by the end of August 2017, 3,685 of which have been awarded since January 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-04T12:18:42.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755550/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755550/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many organisations have completed the Government's Cyber-Essentials Scheme in each year since it was created.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755551","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The CyberFirst programme covers a range of activities; a bursary scheme, development events for students aged between 11-17 and girls only competition. 96 young adults were offered a place on the CyberFirst bursary programme in 2016/2017. 987 students aged between 14-17 attended CyberFirst development events in 2017, and the 2017 girls only CyberFirst events attracted 8000 participants from schools across the UK.   <strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:01:31.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755551/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755551/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many young people have completed the Government's CyberFirst programme.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755552","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>No civil servants have moved, or are planned to move, as a result of the machinery of government changes announced on 20 July 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-30T15:48:47.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755552/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755552/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants will move department due to the machinery of government changes announced on 20 July 2017, broken down by department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755553","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of entrants into the Senior Civil Service since 2010 is as follows:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>New Entrants to the SCS</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Internal</p></td><td><p>External</p></td><td><p>% Internal</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>161</p></td><td><p>102</p></td><td><p>61.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>270</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>72.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>344</p></td><td><p>210</p></td><td><p>62.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>469</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>72.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>456</p></td><td><p>187</p></td><td><p>70.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>562</p></td><td><p>171</p></td><td><p>76.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>549</p></td><td><p>177</p></td><td><p>75.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:16:39.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755553/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755553/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Senior Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, (a) what proportion of and (b) how many appointments to the senior Civil Service were made (i) internally and (ii) externally in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755554","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Due to platform changes for the Civil Service Jobs website, the department only holds central information regarding appointments from April 2014. The information held includes appointments advertised on Civil Service jobs for 39 government departments and organisations. As well as this, the information also includes data from the Civil Service Fast Stream and the Direct Entry Scheme, which is for ‘near miss’ Fast Stream applicants. The information does not include information on Civil Service Fast Track data.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Departments are also able to recruit through third party providers, meaning the Cabinet Office is not able to include these figures in this response. The Cabinet Office will not be including information on appointments to the Senior Civil Service as this will be covered by a separate response to a different Parliamentary Question you have submitted.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>For central records held:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>In 2014, from April of that year, the proportion of appointments in the Civil Service made to internal candidates was 67.9%, with external candidates being 32.1%.</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>In 2015, the proportion of appointments in the Civil Service made to internal candidates was 67.2%, with external candidates being 32.8%.</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>In 2016, the proportion of appointments in the Civil Service made to internal candidates was 63.3%, with external candidates being 37.7%. Please note that these percentages do not include Civil Service Fast Stream or Direct Entry Scheme as these figures are being prepared for future publication.</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:19:23.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755554/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755554/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of appointments in the Civil Service were made (a) internally and (b) externally in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755555","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Strategic Supplier list was most recently updated on 16 August 2017. The list is updated as changes are made to Crown Representatives or as suppliers are added to or removed from the list.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at</p><p>htttps://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Representatives do have other professional duties, which vary depending on the individual. The other professional duties they hold ensure they retain current experience and insight into industry. This allows them to be effective in their Crown Representative capacity. The Cabinet Office has a governance process in place whereby the Crown Representatives declare any conflicts of interests both on appointment and every 6 months.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7345 ; 7346","2017-09-12T13:46:30.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755555/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755555/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government next plans to update its list of strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755556","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The exemption under section 43 of the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) enquiry allows a public authority to withhold information on the grounds that it would or would be likely to prejudice commercial interests.</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Commercial Service has not invoked this exemption for any FOIA relating to the Mystery Shopper Service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-07T15:00:29.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755556/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755556/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of freedom of information requests sent to the Government Mystery Shopper service has been withheld on the grounds that the information requested is commercially sensitive in each year since that service was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755557","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Although the Government is leading by example in best payment practice, we are committed to making further improvements across the public sector, and the Mystery Shopper Service has played an increasingly important role in achieving this.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Mystery Shopper Service has investigated the following cases related to payment issues, including payment terms and late payment, up to 6 September 2017:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (to date)</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:16:35.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755557/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755557/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many reports to the Government Mystery Shopper service have related to non-payment in each year since that service was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755558","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Strategic Supplier list was most recently updated on 16 August 2017. The list is updated as changes are made to Crown Representatives or as suppliers are added to or removed from the list.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at</p><p>htttps://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Representatives do have other professional duties, which vary depending on the individual. The other professional duties they hold ensure they retain current experience and insight into industry. This allows them to be effective in their Crown Representative capacity. The Cabinet Office has a governance process in place whereby the Crown Representatives declare any conflicts of interests both on appointment and every 6 months.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7346 ; 7359","2017-09-12T13:46:31.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755558/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755558/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the value of contracts awarded to Government strategic suppliers was that are listed in the document entitled Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers of July 2017.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755559","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Strategic Supplier list was most recently updated on 16 August 2017. The list is updated as changes are made to Crown Representatives or as suppliers are added to or removed from the list.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at</p><p>htttps://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Representatives do have other professional duties, which vary depending on the individual. The other professional duties they hold ensure they retain current experience and insight into industry. This allows them to be effective in their Crown Representative capacity. The Cabinet Office has a governance process in place whereby the Crown Representatives declare any conflicts of interests both on appointment and every 6 months.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7345 ; 7359","2017-09-12T13:46:31.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755559/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755559/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Crown Representatives listed in the Government's List of Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers of July 2017 have any other professional duties.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755560","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>Each department, agency or public body is responsible for managing the cyber security of their own organisation’s internet access, including the use of web filters and security tools. The UK’s cyber security technical authority, the National Cyber Security Centre, provides guidance to departments on how to secure their internet access.</p><p> </p><p>The NCSC has also developed Active Cyber Defence measures some of which are available to the public sector. One measure is DNS (Domain Name System) filtering that blocks registered public sector organisations from accessing sites that are known to contain malware or are fraudulent. As of August 2017, the service is up and running with 44 government organisations actively blocking users from accessing insecure domains.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-14T12:10:27.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755560/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755560/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, by what means the Government ensures the cyber security of its departments, agencies or other public bodies that use websites other than those on gov.uk.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755561","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Since publication of the 2016 National Cyber Security Strategy, we have been working with experts in Departments, Agencies, academia and industry to develop an interim Cyber Security Science and Technology strategy, which we plan to publish this autumn. The interim strategy sets out our broad approach and establishes the responsibilities, structure and processes needed to develop a full strategy for publication in April 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-07T15:04:43.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755561/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755561/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress is being made on the development of the detailed Cyber Science and Technology strategy referred to in paragraph 7.3.5 of the Government's 2016 National Cyber Security Strategy.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755562","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Civil Service aims to be as transparent as possible, and already discloses a significant amount of senior pay data. The Office for National Statistics publishes a range of detailed pay information in its annual release of Civil Service Statistics, including the number of staff earning over £100,000 and other pay information. The latest release is available at:<br>https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/civilservicestatistics</p><p>In addition, since 2010 the Government has published an annual list of individuals in departments, agencies and Non-departmental Public Bodies earning £150,000 and above. Departments also publish organograms every six months that include individualised salary information for their most senior staff</p><p>Relevant departments are responsible for transparency policy in wider public sector workforces.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T12:15:56.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755562/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755562/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment the Government has made of publishing details of all public sector pay above the £100,000 threshold for which it holds the relevant information.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","7458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755563","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>National Cyber Security Programme funding is allocated on a yearly basis in line with financial years. In FY 16/17 government invested £229m of the £1.9bn to support key projects set out in the NCSS, including:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>Establishing the National Cyber Security Centre,</p></li><li><p>Producing a series of Active Cyber Defence measures which are currently helping to defend public sector systems against cyber attacks, and</p></li><li><p>Developing cyber security industry and skills through creating Innovation Centres and supporting the successful CyberFirst Programme.</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:55:14.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755563/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755563/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Government has invested in the UK's cyber security in the last six months; and on what projects the £1.9 billion of funding outlined in the National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 has been spent.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755564","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Deterring and disrupting hostile cyber activity against the UK is an important objective of the National Cyber Security Strategy. Good progress is being made by GCHQ, including the newly established National Cyber Security Centre, and the Ministry of Defence and the National Crime Agency in developing world-class capabilities and skills for this purpose. This activity is being conducted under the auspices of the National Offensive Cyber Programme and the National Cyber Security Programme.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:16:26.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755564/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755564/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress is being made on the Government's aim to increase the scale and development of GCHQ, Ministry of Defence and National Crime Agency capabilities to disrupt the most serious cyber threats to the UK as set out in paragraph 5.1.3 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755565","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government’s National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) is developing an operational capability to exchange cyber threat information at scale, using open standards, with organisations in the UK and international partners. Following an initial trial, NCSC is evaluating a number of commercial offerings, and their integration into NCSC’s threat-intelligence systems, to ensure the effective delivery of this capability.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:15:02.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755565/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755565/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government is making on moving towards automated information sharing so that cyber security systems automatically alert each other to incidents or attacks, as set out in paragraph 5.6.8 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755566","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>The cyber security skills advisory group has been formed, but is only part of the solution. Since publication of the National Cyber Security Strategy in 2016, my officials have regularly met with, and sought advice on cyber skills from, a wide range of representatives of industry, academic and professional organisations in order to develop policy and see how else government can help to close the cyber skills gap.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-04T12:19:49.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755566/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755566/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on the establishment of a skills advisory group to close the cyber skills gap in the UK workforce as set out in paragraph 7.1.8 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755567","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) provides advice and guidance to citizens and organisations through a wide range of means including its website, events, bespoke engagement and the Cyber Information Sharing Partnership (CISP).</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Government also issues advice on the simple steps that individuals and small businesses can take to protect themselves through its ‘CyberAware’ campaign, delivered in partnership with industry, the third sector and law enforcement.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We continually seek to improve the quality and relevance of all advice.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:25:12.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755567/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755567/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government is making on (a) providing the advice that the economy needs to protect itself and (b) improving how that advice is given in order to maximise its effect as set out in paragraph 5.5.3 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755568","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>‘Secure by Default’ refers to solving security problems at root; acting at scale to reduce the harm to online systems. There is no target figure due to the magnitude of online products and services. The National Cyber Security Centre is developing secure systems so that the burden on users to make the right decisions is reduced. Additionally, the Department of Digital, Culture, Media and Sport is currently leading a comprehensive review on how we can improve the security of consumer connected devices and services.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:12:18.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755568/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755568/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the target figure is for the objective relating to the number of online products and services coming into use being secure by default  by 2021 as set out in objective 5.2.3 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755569","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>HMG uses a mature risk management process to balance functionality, security, risk and cost</p><p>Through this process Risk Owners determine the risks they are willing to tolerate to their services,<br>largely based on potential impact, and make sure that appropriate mitigations are in place. The<br>National Cyber Security Centre publishes advice on cyber risk management and technical design<br>principles to help service owners make consistent risk decisions.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T10:13:41.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755569/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755569/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the Government's definition is of the acceptable risk parameters for the cyber security of all Government services referred to in paragraph 5.2.7 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755570","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The government's Active Cyber Defence (ACD) programme has launched, with four key services already used by Departments to protect their online services. This in turn protects the citizen by reducing the risk of malicious content reaching victims, such as email fraud from criminals posing as government departments. The ACD programme is also working with the private sector to actively take down phishing sites, which will also reduce the likelihood of the citizen being tricked by criminals online.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:14:53.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755570/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755570/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress is being made on the Government's aim to provide automated protections for Government online services to the citizen as set out in paragraph 5.1.3 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755571","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) has made significant progress in developing<br>the government’s ability to disrupt cyber threats. Four Active Cyber Defence services are<br>currently live and free at the point of use for the public sector. These provide measures to<br>defeat a significant proportion of commodity attacks that affect UK interests. Next year the<br>NCSC will be scaling these services and developing models to make them more widely<br>available to public and private sector organisations.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T15:00:36.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755571/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755571/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government is making on increasing the scale and development of its own capabilities to disrupt the most serious cyber threats as set out in paragraph 5.1.3 of the Government's National Cyber Security Strategy 2016 to 2021.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755572","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government and I are jointly responsible for the Race Disparity Audit. The timing of the Audit was agreed by the Government collectively. The Audit will be published in the Autumn, 2017.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-09-07T15:06:36.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755572/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755572/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who is responsible for the timetable on publishing the findings of the Government's race audit of public services.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","7523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755573","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Committee on Standards in Public Life is an independent, advisory, standing body sponsored by the Cabinet Office. The Committee sets its own work programme. The Committee on Standards in Public Life is following up its 2014 report on Ethical Standards for Public Service Providers and 2015 guidance</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p><p>As part of its research, the Committee has met with organisations that provide public services, some commissioners and other think tanks and groups interested in this topic.</p><p> </p><p>Attendees at the roundtable on 20 March 2017 were the Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations, Institute of Business Ethics, Institute for Government, National Council for Voluntary Organisations, Federation of Small Businesses, Public Services Lab, Business Services Association, CBI, Centre for Public Scrutiny and the General Pharmaceutical Council.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee intends to publish its follow up report later this year.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7547 ; 7548 ; 7549","2017-09-07T15:13:18.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755573/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755573/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Committee on Standards in Public Life","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what was discussed at the meeting between Capital and the Committee for Standards in Public Life in their meeting on 11 April 2017; and what work of that committee has arisen from that meeting.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755574","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Committee on Standards in Public Life is an independent, advisory, standing body sponsored by the Cabinet Office. The Committee sets its own work programme. The Committee on Standards in Public Life is following up its 2014 report on Ethical Standards for Public Service Providers and 2015 guidance</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p><p>As part of its research, the Committee has met with organisations that provide public services, some commissioners and other think tanks and groups interested in this topic.</p><p> </p><p>Attendees at the roundtable on 20 March 2017 were the Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations, Institute of Business Ethics, Institute for Government, National Council for Voluntary Organisations, Federation of Small Businesses, Public Services Lab, Business Services Association, CBI, Centre for Public Scrutiny and the General Pharmaceutical Council.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee intends to publish its follow up report later this year.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7546 ; 7548 ; 7549","2017-09-07T15:13:18.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755574/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755574/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Committee on Standards in Public Life","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what was discussed at the meeting between G4S and the Committee for Standards in Public Life in their meeting on 15 March 2017; and what work of that committee has arisen from that meeting.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755575","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Committee on Standards in Public Life is an independent, advisory, standing body sponsored by the Cabinet Office. The Committee sets its own work programme. The Committee on Standards in Public Life is following up its 2014 report on Ethical Standards for Public Service Providers and 2015 guidance</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p><p>As part of its research, the Committee has met with organisations that provide public services, some commissioners and other think tanks and groups interested in this topic.</p><p> </p><p>Attendees at the roundtable on 20 March 2017 were the Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations, Institute of Business Ethics, Institute for Government, National Council for Voluntary Organisations, Federation of Small Businesses, Public Services Lab, Business Services Association, CBI, Centre for Public Scrutiny and the General Pharmaceutical Council.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee intends to publish its follow up report later this year.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7546 ; 7547 ; 7549","2017-09-07T15:13:18.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755575/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755575/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Committee on Standards in Public Life","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what was discussed at the meeting between Serco and the Committee for Standards in Public Life in their meeting on 2 March 2017; and what work of that committee has arisen from that meeting.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755576","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) use SMS to provide acknowledgment of receipt for all tax credit renewals where there is a valid mobile phone number held. In addition, this year HMRC offered e-mail acknowledgments to all customers submitting their renewal online through the digital service.</p><p>Only after making significant efforts to obtain a reply from the customer would HMRC seek to stop tax credit payments.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T13:39:34.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755576/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755576/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the merits of requiring HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to send an automatic acknowledgement to tax credit claimants who submit their renewals online; and if he will make it HMRC policy to not suspend tax credit claims until HMRC have evidence that claimants have received and then failed to respond to their communications.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755577","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK allocation from the Fund for European Aid to the Most Deprived (FEAD) was €3.94m for the 2014-20 period. In 2014, the Government indicated that because the UK allocation from the fund is deducted from our European Social Fund and the European Regional Development Fund allocations, it would minimise the adverse impact on those funds by taking the lowest possible allocation.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, the Government announced that its FEAD allocation would be used to expand breakfast club provision in deprived areas in England. The Department for Education received interim funding of €433,912.60 in 2014 in advance of the scheme commencing. This is the only payment we have received.</p><p><br>After we had publicly committed to the scheme in 2014, the EC began detailed discussions on the regulations which govern how the money can be spent. It has since become clear that our original vision for how to use this funding cannot comply with the EC’s eligibility requirements for the fund. We are therefore discussing with Her Majesty’s Treasury about how we can best apply this money before we leave the European Union.</p><p>The Government has delivered significantly higher funding for breakfast clubs than that envisaged by the FEAD. DfE ran a two year £1.1m programme which ended in March 2016 which saw breakfast clubs implemented in 184 schools with a high proportion of disadvantaged pupils. In the 2016 Budget, the Chancellor announced further funding of £10m a year to set up breakfast clubs in up to 1600 schools. Further details of the programme will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-12T16:19:28.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755577/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755577/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Disadvantaged: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how the Government has allocated funds from the Fund for European Aid to the Most Deprived in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755578","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>Proposals to use public resources are required to be put forward in a Business Case which must be prepared in accordance with the Green Book. Green Book analysis is therefore the foundation of the scrutiny and approval process.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:30:54.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755578/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755578/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what methods his Department has adopted to monitor and encourage compliance with the best practice set out in his Department's Green Book.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755579","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government routinely makes adjustments to public spending throughout the year and will deal with the cost of additional resources for the Northern Ireland Executive within our overall plans in this way.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:10:53.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755579/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755579/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, from which part of the Government's budget the £1.5 billion package of funding attributed to the supply and confidence deal with the Democratic Unionist Party came; and whether the funding for that deal had any implications for other spending commitments.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","7464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755580","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The government established an independent <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_Policy_Committee" target="_blank">Financial Policy Committee</a> (FPC), giving the FPC a primary objective to identify, monitor and take action to remove or reduce systemic risks with a view to protecting and enhancing financial stability. Following its most recent policy meeting on 21 June, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FPC" target="_blank">FPC</a> published the Financial Stability Report (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FSR" target="_blank">FSR</a>). The FSR assessed recent trends in the consumer credit market including dealership car finance. The FSR noted that consumer credit and dealership car finance has been growing rapidly, but that loss rates on consumer credit lending are low at present.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:46:18.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755580/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755580/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Cars: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the risks to the economy posed by the growth of personal contract purchase finance deals for new car sales.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","7385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755581","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The research on the effects of transparency in overseas money transfers (involving foreign exchange) on consumer decisions helped to inform the Government’s response to its consultation on the implementation of the second Payment Services Directive (PSDII), which was published on 19 July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Government did not include a requirement in the Payment Services Regulations 2017 for increased transparency as it had to weigh up the potential benefits of doing so against other issues, such as the Government’s approach to implementing maximum harmonising Directives.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:08:54.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755581/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755581/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Payments: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, whether his Department's research on the effect of pricing structures on consumer understanding of foreign currency transaction fees will inform the Payment Services Regulations.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","7401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755582","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held. However some relevant information on landlords in PAYE but not registered for self-assessment is available in the Measuring tax gaps methodological annex at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps</a></p><p>Please refer to table H.5 on page 55.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:40:57.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755582/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755582/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Landlords: Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the amount of tax revenue lost through landlords not (a) properly declaring rent and (b) registering for self-assessment.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755583","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has conducted analysis of over 50 sectors of the economy, including financial services.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has recently published a series of papers, and will be publishing further papers, which set out the UK’s approach to our new deep and special partnership with the EU. These papers are designed to provide citizens and businesses at home and across Europe with a deeper understanding of our thinking and draw on the extensive and diverse engagement the Government has sought from external parties.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:27:30.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755583/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755583/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has undertaken an impact assessment of the effect on the UK financial sector of the UK leaving the single market.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","6874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755584","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Treasury intends to publish a refreshed edition of the Green Book later this year.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:29:15.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755584/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755584/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he intends to publish updates to the Treasury Green Book.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755585","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government will set out its plans in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7734","2017-09-07T14:14:03.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755585/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755585/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","National Insurance Contributions: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, by what date he intends to implement a national insurance contributions exemption for businesses employing ex-offenders.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755586","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>There is no special rate or calculation of VAT that applies specifically to cosmetic services. If the primary purpose of the treatment is for the protection, maintenance or restoration of the health of the individual, then no VAT will be charged on the procedure. VAT is charged at the standard rate on other cosmetic services.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-07T14:18:09.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755586/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755586/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Plastic Surgery: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how the rate of VAT payable for cosmetic surgery procedures is calculated.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","6972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755587","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold information on VAT revenues from charities that can be broken down to the requested level of detail.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T12:55:07.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755587/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755587/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Charities: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the rate of VAT collected from accident rescue charities in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","6945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755588","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>As set out in the Prime Minister's Article 50 letter we want to avoid a return to a hard border between our two countries, and to be able to maintain the Common Travel Area. The deeply integrated nature of trade, both domestically between Northern Ireland and Great Britain, and across the land border between Northern Ireland and Ireland, highlights why the UK is prioritising finding a solution that protects businesses’ ability to access these markets. We welcome the Commission's position paper on Northern Ireland and Ireland, in particular the commitment to avoid any physical infrastructure at the border, agreeing with the UK’s position as published last month. This is an important step forward, and demonstrates the close alignment on the UK’s and EU’s objectives on this issue.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:48:38.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755588/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755588/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Borders: Northern Ireland and Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the economic effect of establishment of a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755589","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer meets with EU officials on a regular basis, including at the Economic and Financial Affairs Council (ECOFIN) and other international fora, where they discuss a range of policy issues. Details of ministers’ overseas travel is published quarterly and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a>.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:45:15.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755589/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755589/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings he has had with EU officials since 8 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755590","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The cost of protecting income and gains that arise and remain within a non-resident trust which is set up by a non-domiciled individual who later becomes deemed-UK domiciled form part of the wider package costed as part of the non-dom reforms. The figures for the full package are set out in Table 2.2 of Spring Budget 2017 under two rows: “Non-domiciles: abolish permanent status” and “Non-domicile: IHT on UK residential property. They have been certified by the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Measure</p></td><td><p>2017 to 2018</p></td><td><p>2018 to 2019</p></td><td><p>2019 to 2020</p></td><td><p>2020 to 2021</p></td><td><p>2021 to 2022</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-dom: abolish permanent status</p></td><td><p>-£20m</p></td><td><p>£410m</p></td><td><p>£330m</p></td><td><p>£315m</p></td><td><p>£310m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-dom: IHT on UK residential property</p></td><td><p>£25m</p></td><td><p>£80m</p></td><td><p>£50m</p></td><td><p>£55m</p></td><td><p>£65m</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:39:43.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755590/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755590/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Domicil","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of protecting overseas trusts in the draft provisions on deemed domicile for tax purposes.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755591","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>Working age inactivity is estimated by the independent Office for National Statistics (ONS).</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/august2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/august2017</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","7092","2017-09-11T14:32:02.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755591/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755591/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the level of people currently defined as economically inactive.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755592","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>Working age inactivity is estimated by the independent Office for National Statistics (ONS).</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/august2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/august2017</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","7096","2017-09-11T14:32:02.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755592/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755592/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many economically inactive people there were in the UK in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d), 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015, (g) 2016 and (h) 2017.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755593","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK is seeking multilateral agreement on a model of public country-by-country reporting (CBCR).</p><p> </p><p>It is important that there is a level of international support and co-ordination that leads to both domestic and foreign headquartered groups being required to report information for a comprehensive range of countries in which they operate.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has raised public CBCR with international partners and will continue to do so, including at EU level.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains determined to get the very best deal for businesses and households during the negotiations with the EU.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7759","2017-09-12T12:43:30.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755593/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755593/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects to implement public country-by-country reporting.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755594","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The transfer pricing rules set out how transactions between connected parties are priced for tax purposes. In common with most countries the UK rules are based on the internationally recognized arm’s length principle. HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) challenges arrangements that do not allocate the right amount of profits to the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has led the way in taking action to ensure multinational companies pay their fair share of taxes. We played a critical role in establishing the OECD project to strengthen international tax standards to help counter base erosion and profit shifting.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has gone further by taking a lead in the implementation of measures to address that profit shifting, for example, introducing the Diverted Profits Tax (DPT). This measure encourages businesses that are using contrived arrangements to minimise their tax liabilities, to change those behaviours or face paying tax at a higher rate.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC deploys specialist staff to deal with international tax risks, including transfer pricing and diversion of profits. These experts work with other industry experts and tax specialists to tackle all international tax issues that represent substantial risk of tax loss to the Exchequer. HMRC also works with other tax authorities, sharing information and expertise, to identify risk and challenge arrangements. The recent introduction of Country by Country reporting will also increase the information available to HMRC and assist their risk assessment processes to identify these tax risks.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T12:53:05.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755594/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755594/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Multinational Companies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to prevent multinational companies using the transfer pricing method to avoid paying taxes.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755595","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Apprenticeship Levy was introduced on a UK wide basis from 6 April 2017. Employers are charged at 0.5% of their pay bill over £3 million. Information on how much Apprenticeship Levy individual employers pay, such as Welsh police forces, cannot be made publicly available because of tax payer confidentiality.</p><p> </p><p>Skills policy is devolved and the devolved administrations will receive a population share of the Office for Budget Responsibility’s March 2016 forecast of revenue from the levy. In 2017-18, the Welsh Government will receive £128 million.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:25:25.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755595/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755595/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been collected from Welsh police forces through the apprenticeship levy; and how much of that has been passed on to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","7078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755596","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>UK Officials in the Department for International Trade, the Department for Exiting the EU, the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office have met officials of the Republic of Turkey where discussion on this matter were held.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:29:39.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755596/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755596/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Turkey: Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he or officials of his Department have had with the Turkish Government about that country's customs agreement with the EU.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","7100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755597","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The guidance referenced is now archived and the most relevant guidance is “UK economic statistics sector and transaction classifications: the classification process” on the Office for National Statistics website <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/methodology/classificationsandstandards/economicstatisticsclassifications/ukeconomicstatisticssectorandtransactionclassificationstheclassificationprocess" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/methodology/classificationsandstandards/economicstatisticsclassifications/ukeconomicstatisticssectorandtransactionclassificationstheclassificationprocess</a> Section 6 of the paper - Government Policy Proposals states – “Most policy proposals are in a near-final form when presented to ONS and will include all the relevant details to enable ONS to make a judgement. Any classification decision based on a near-final policy proposal will be deemed as “provisional” and dependent on the proposal being implemented as described. If the circumstances change, it is the responsibility of the proposing department to inform ONS via the HM Treasury Public Expenditure Classification Branch.</p><p>However, on rare occasions, government departments might seek a view on a proposal at an early stage of development. In such cases, ONS will provide provisional advice on the expected classification of the proposal, based on information available at the time. This is subject to the qualification that a final decision will not be reached until such a time as the policy is implemented. In the interim, ONS will only consider alternative versions of the same proposal exceptionally and if substantial and significant changes have been made. Any explanatory article published on the final policy proposal will note how many versions of the proposal ONS considered. Final classification decisions will be published when the policy has been announced or implemented by the government.”</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T14:18:32.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755597/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755597/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Office for National Statistics","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the issuing of a provisional ruling by the Office of National Statistics (ONS) as set out in section 6 paragraph 49 of the ONS Classification Process Guidelines, January 2016, requires all relevant documentation to be in near-final form and for a decision in principle in favour of Government support to have been made.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","7076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755598","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The guidance referenced is now archived and the most relevant guidance is “UK economic statistics sector and transaction classifications: the classification process” on the Office for National Statistics website <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/methodology/classificationsandstandards/economicstatisticsclassifications/ukeconomicstatisticssectorandtransactionclassificationstheclassificationprocess" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/methodology/classificationsandstandards/economicstatisticsclassifications/ukeconomicstatisticssectorandtransactionclassificationstheclassificationprocess</a> Section 6 of the paper - Government Policy Proposals states – “Most policy proposals are in a near-final form when presented to ONS and will include all the relevant details to enable ONS to make a judgement. Any classification decision based on a near-final policy proposal will be deemed as “provisional” and dependent on the proposal being implemented as described. If the circumstances change, it is the responsibility of the proposing department to inform ONS via the HM Treasury Public Expenditure Classification Branch.</p><p>However, on rare occasions, government departments might seek a view on a proposal at an early stage of development. In such cases, ONS will provide provisional advice on the expected classification of the proposal, based on information available at the time. This is subject to the qualification that a final decision will not be reached until such a time as the policy is implemented. In the interim, ONS will only consider alternative versions of the same proposal exceptionally and if substantial and significant changes have been made. Any explanatory article published on the final policy proposal will note how many versions of the proposal ONS considered. Final classification decisions will be published when the policy has been announced or implemented by the government.”</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T13:27:46.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755598/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755598/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Office for National Statistics","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the issuing of provisional advice on the expected classification of a proposal at an early stage of development as set out in section 6 paragraph 49 of the Office for National Statistics Classification Process Guidelines, January 2016, is dependent upon all relevant documentation being in a near-final form and a decision in principle to offer Government support having been made.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","7077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755599","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The apprenticeship levy was introduced from 6 April 2017 and is payable by all employers operating in the UK with an annual pay bill over £3 million.</p><p> </p><p>Skills policy is devolved and the devolved administrations will receive a population share of the Office for Budget Responsibility’s March 2016 forecast of revenue from the levy. In 2017-18, the Welsh Government will receive £128 million.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:23:14.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755599/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755599/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much from the apprenticeship levy has been given to the Welsh Government since the levy came into force.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","7079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755600","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>At the 2015 Spending Review, the Government set a funding envelope for High Speed 2 Phase Two of £28.55bn in 2015 prices</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:54:56.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755600/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755600/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost of the second phase of High Speed 2 from Birmingham to Manchester and Leeds.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755601","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>At the 2015 Spending Review, the Government restated the long-term funding envelope for delivery of the full High Speed 2 scheme of £55.7bn in 2015 prices.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:57:23.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755601/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755601/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755602","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>My Department works closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in developing the Government’s response to the shared challenges of improving air quality and reducing greenhouse gas emissions. The Government announced an intention to end the sale of all new conventional cars and vans by 2040 as part of the ‘UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide concentrations’ (July 2017). My Department engaged closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Department for Transport and other relevant departments to draft and agree this Plan, including at Ministerial level.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:08:18.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755602/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755602/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department had with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs before the announcement of a ban on petrol and diesel vehicles by 2040.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","7177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755603","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The number of civil servants for each of the years requested can be found in the annual report and accounts which can be accessed via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-annual-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-annual-report</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-11T16:11:22.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755603/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755603/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil servants were based in his Department in each year from 2010 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755604","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Where the valuation of a non-domestic property is altered following a successful appeal, the ratepayer will generally receive a backdated refund. Local authorities also have wide-ranging powers to provide discretionary rate relief to businesses in their area, including where a business is experiencing significant financial hardship. From April 2017, the Government introduced reforms to the appeals system to help reduce the delays caused by large numbers of speculative appeals.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","7267","2017-09-12T11:03:31.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755604/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755604/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 900568, what compensation is available for businesses that win at appeal but have suffered losses between the original valuation and appeal.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","7266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755605","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Where the valuation of a non-domestic property is altered following a successful appeal, the ratepayer will generally receive a backdated refund. Local authorities also have wide-ranging powers to provide discretionary rate relief to businesses in their area, including where a business is experiencing significant financial hardship. From April 2017, the Government introduced reforms to the appeals system to help reduce the delays caused by large numbers of speculative appeals.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","7266","2017-09-12T11:03:31.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755605/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755605/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 900568, what support is available to businesses that have had their property incorrectly valued by the Valuation Office Agency.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","7267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755606","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The estimated cost of investment to deliver and run the Customs Declaration Service up to 2022 is £133 million, reflecting total development and operating costs as published in the National Audit Office report in July 2017. The estimated cost is based on latest 2017 Outline Business Case.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:31:03.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755606/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755606/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Customs Declaration Services Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost of the creation and first five years of running the Customs Declarations Services programme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755607","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) Customs Declaration Service (CDS) programme has been reviewed by the Infrastructure &amp; Projects Authority and the National Audit Office. These plans are on track but not without risk, as is normal for any programme of this size, and contingency planning has been carried out to ensure the successful delivery of the new CDS system without significant impact on the smooth running of the UK’s international trade.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has a strategy for moving customers to CDS. This has been reached through extensive stakeholder and customer engagement, working closely with key partners in international trade. Our guiding design principles are to ensure minimal change to processes and minimal disruption to operations to reduce burdens on business. There is still a year to go before customers will start transitioning to the new CDS system.</p><p> </p><p>The timetable for implementation has been discussed and influenced by trade partners and key customers to fit with their preferred lead in times where changes to their systems were unavoidable.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:38:06.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755607/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755607/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Customs Declaration Services Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the economic effect of the time taken to implement the Customs Declarations Services programme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755608","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>In the vast majority of cases the necessary approvals are sought in advance. Though retrospective approvals do sometimes occur, a central record is not kept of the numbers. It would therefore require disproportionate resources to fully gather the required information‎.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:19:18.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755608/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755608/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many times retrospective permission for spending has been (a) requested and (b) granted by his Department in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755609","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The exit payment cap will apply to organisations classified as within the public sector by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) with limited exceptions. As AWE [Atomic Weapons Establishment] Management Ltd is classified by the ONS as a public sector organisation it is within scope of the reforms.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T15:33:33.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755609/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755609/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Atomic Weapons Research Establishment: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons employees of the management company running the Atomic Weapons Establishment are considered private sector employees for the purpose of pensions but public sector employees for the purpose of the exit payment cap.","false","Biography information for Richard Benyon","Newbury","Richard Benyon","7292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755610","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) Customer Compliance Group (CCG) are responsible for the majority of the enforcement and compliance type activity and have carried out successful campaign activity in the rental sector, however HMRC are unable to answer the specific question without incurring disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC launched the Let Property Campaign in 2013; it is focused on the residential property letting market. It aims to help landlords to get their tax right from day one, keeping them on track, and offering an opportunity to address previous errors. It is highly successful at both providing educational material to prevent tax loss and enabling landlords to bring their affairs up to date. It has raised over £115m in additional tax, interest and penalties to December 2016.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:22:52.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755610/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755610/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Landlords: Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many landlords in the UK are currently persons of interest to HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755611","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The only bilateral loan which the UK government has provided since 2010 is the bilateral loan to Ireland. Information about this loan is provided in the most recent statutory report which the Treasury provided to Parliament as required by Section 2 of the Loans to Ireland Act 2010. The last report was laid in Parliament on 18 April 2017 and is available in the Printed Paper Office.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T09:58:20.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755611/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755611/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many bilateral loans his Department has made since 2010; what amount was loaned in each case; and what amount has been paid back in each case.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755612","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>Scotch whisky producers are currently eligible to apply for EU funding under the Scottish Rural Development Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The UK government has provided guarantees for rural development and agri-environment schemes that are signed before the UK leaves the EU. We are offering the devolved administrations the same level of reassurance as we are offering to UK government departments in relation to programmes they administer but for which they expected to rely on EU funding.</p><p>In the longer term, decisions on funding will be taken in light of wider UK strategic priorities and other domestic spending decisions.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:07:13.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755612/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755612/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if the Government will match EU funding levels for the Scotch whisky industry to fund the promotion of food and drink geographical indications or protected designations of origin and rural development after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755613","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. We will seek to achieve the right deal for Britain and for the EU.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:14:10.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755613/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755613/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to change alcohol taxation structures and levels after the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755614","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>There is no tax credit legislation allowing debt from the Department for Work and Pensions to be recovered from Child Tax Credit payments.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-11T14:53:33.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755614/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755614/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many child tax credit claimants in (a) Glasgow city, (b) Scotland and (c) the UK are having deductions made from child tax credit payments to service existing debts to the Department for Work and Pensions.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755615","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Hon member to my previous responses on this subject (3735; 3736; 3737; 3738)</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:21:44.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755615/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755615/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to update the UK's tax treaty with Malawi.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755616","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Government will consider this issue in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going work to review building safety.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-20T13:16:02.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755616/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755616/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Fire Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question HL374, whether an assessment has been made of the extent to which his Department's Approved Document B is effective as a means by which the functional requirements of fire safety may be met.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755617","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework makes clear the importance of planning for safe and accessible environments while our planning guidance states that streets should be designed to be functional and accessible for all and not just respond to engineering considerations.</p><p>Licensing for advertising, street furniture and parking is a responsibility for each local authority.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:41:53.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755617/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755617/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Pedestrian Areas: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proposals his Department plans to put in place to ensure that disabled people are better able to move freely along street pavements without obstruction from cars, street furniture and advertising materials.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755618","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to collaborating with the local government sector in developing the future direction of local government finance reform. Dialogue between the Local Government Association and the Government is ongoing and I have recently written to the Chair of the Local Government Association proposing that the steering and working groups continue to work with the Government.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:46:22.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755618/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755618/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Local Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 5261, when the Government plans to make a decision on how best to continue to engage the Local Government Association, the steering and working groups and the local government sector more generally.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755619","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) regularly assesses the level of threat posed to a wide range of organisations. The NCSC also works with other organisations, including the Charity Commission, to ensure that assessment information, tailored advice, and guidance is provided to organisations where appropriate and relevant.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:36:54.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755619/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755619/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Local Government: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment the Government has made of the level of threat posed by cyber attacks to charities or third sector bodies contracted to do work for local authorities or providing a public service in conjunction with those authorities.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755620","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>We have already taken steps to tackle unfair practices by private parking operators, including the banning of wheel clamping and towing.</p><p>My Department is also considering reforms of the private parking sector and we are keen to ensure motorists get fair treatment from private parking companies.</p><p>We welcome the Rt Hon Sir Greg Knight’s Private Member's Bill that seeks to create an independent code of practice for private parking companies. We look forward to reading Sir Greg’s recommendations.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:36:05.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755620/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755620/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Parking: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to tackle the practices of rogue private parking operators.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","7201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755621","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>In the period 1 January 2010 to 30 June 2017, 275 appeals were decided for the unitary authority Northumberland County Council and a further 8 for the Northumberland National Park Authority (NPA). All those for the NPA were decided by Inspectors under delegated powers. 9 of the 275 for the unitary authority were decided by the Secretary of State, with the remainder by Inspectors under delegated powers.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T14:09:56.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755621/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755621/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Planning Permission: Northumberland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many planning appeals from Northumberland have been heard by Ministers since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","7204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755622","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>Supported housing supports many vulnerable people, including those with disabilities, to live independently. That is why we have committed to providing £400 million of funding announced in the Department for Communities and Local Government’s Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme to deliver affordable homes for the vulnerable, elderly and those with disabilities. Furthermore, the Department of Health has committed £224.5 million to date through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund. Since 2011, we have delivered 27,000 units of specialist and general housing for disabled, vulnerable and older people.</p><p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans in the autumn.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:40:35.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755622/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755622/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to increase the level of funding for the supply of specialist housing to meet the needs of disabled people and wheelchair users.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755623","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>Local authorities are best placed to understand the housing needs in their area. National policy sets out clearly the need for local planning authorities to plan for the housing needs of all members of the community and it is for Durham County Council to work closely with key partners and local communities in deciding what type of housing is needed to meet local need, including bungalows. <br> <br> We have published a data sheet setting out information and statistics on older and disabled peoples’ needs to act as a starting point for local authorities wishing to develop suitable policies.</p><p>Our Housing White Paper sets out two ways in which the planning system will be used to deliver more suitable homes for people with disabilities:</p><ul><li>We are proposing to strengthen the National Planning Policy Framework so that local planning authorities are expected to have clear policies for addressing the housing requirements of groups with particular needs, such as disabled people; and</li></ul><ul><li>The Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017 introduced a new statutory duty on the Secretary of State to produce guidance for local planning authorities on how their local development documents should meet the housing needs of older and disabled people.</li></ul>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:47:38.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755623/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755623/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing: Durham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the number of bungalows required to meet the health needs of wheelchair users and people with disabilities in East Durham.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755624","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Home Office has regular discussions with a range of partners including, the Local Government Association (LGA) on the use of the anti-social behaviour powers, including Public Spaces Protection Order, and the LGA is a member of the ASB Advisory Group which monitors the impact of the powers.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T13:52:23.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755624/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755624/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Public Spaces Protection Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions her Department has had with the Local Government Association on the use of public space protection orders.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755625","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has not made any assessment on the impact of Public Spaces Protection Orders on levels of crime. These orders are flexible and local in nature and designed to deal with problems in a specific area where anti-social behaviour has a detrimental effect on the quality of lives of those living locally. Local councils and agencies are best placed to monitor the use of these powers to ensure that the local community can feel safe and enjoy public spaces free from antisocial behaviour.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T13:56:33.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755625/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755625/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Public Spaces Protection Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the use of public space protection orders and the effect of those orders on the level of crimes in the same locations where such orders have been imposed.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) has not undertaken any health and safety assessments on cladding and external wall insulation systems on buildings over 18 metres high in the last seven years. Such assessments are not required by health and safety at work legislation.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-07T13:46:35.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755626/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 25 July 2017 to Question 5348, how many health and safety assessments on cladding and external wall insulation systems have been carried out by the Health and Safety Executive on buildings over 18 metres high in the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755627","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>In 2012, prior to the recommendations made by the Coroner into the Lakanal House fire, research was undertaken into fire safety issues as a first step to simplifying Approved Document B. This was followed by a study of users views of Approved Document B, commissioned in Summer 2015, as well as work to prepare a version of the document in a new, more user friendly style.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T15:00:51.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755627/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755627/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755627/answer/previousversion/8971","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Fire Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 4446, on what date work began on simplifying the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations Approved Document B.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755628","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>As of 10 September 2017 the Building Research Establishment had received 1523 samples to be tested under the Government’s screening programme.</p><p>All 538 samples which were Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding have been tested and landlords informed of the result. The remaining samples were not ACM and therefore outside the scope of the Government’s screening programme.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:35:45.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755628/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755628/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 4915, on Grenfell Tower: Fires, how many cladding samples were tested during the initial testing phase; and if he will publish the results of those tests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755629","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>The initial screening tests are continuing as more building owners send samples of Aluminium Composite Material to the Buildings Research Establishment for testing. The Department for Communities and Local Government publishes details of all items of expenditure over £250 every month and these costs will be included in these publications.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T12:49:03.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755629/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755629/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 4915, on Grenfell Tower: Fires, what the cost of initial testing of samples of cladding material after the Grenfell Tower fire was.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755630","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government will consider the removal of financial restrictions where financial barriers stand in the way of essential work being done. Essential work would include circumstances where local fire services advise essential fire safety works are required to make a building safe. We will work with local authorities who approach us on a case by case basis.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T12:50:29.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755630/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755630/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Council Housing: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 4988, on council housing: repairs and maintenance, what criteria will be used to determine whether local authorities lack financial resources that would prevent refurbishment work going ahead.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755631","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-08","<p>A total of 228 responses were received to the Further Consultation on 100 per cent Business Rates Retention; 187 from local government, 7 from local authority associations, and 34 from other interested parties. The Department for Communities and Local Government is currently conducting analysis of these responses. This will inform further development of business rates retention policy. We are currently considering how this work will progress in the wider context of further rates retention policy.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","7189","2017-09-08T14:41:09.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755631/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755631/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 5262, on non-domestic rates, how many responses were received to the consultation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755632","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-08","<p>A total of 228 responses were received to the Further Consultation on 100 per cent Business Rates Retention; 187 from local government, 7 from local authority associations, and 34 from other interested parties. The Department for Communities and Local Government is currently conducting analysis of these responses. This will inform further development of business rates retention policy. We are currently considering how this work will progress in the wider context of further rates retention policy.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","7188","2017-09-08T14:41:09.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755632/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755632/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 5262, on non-domestic rates, when the Government plans to publish a response to the consultation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755633","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Supported housing supports many vulnerable people, including those with mental health problems, to live independently. Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. Ability to pay rent will depend on a range of circumstances. Those who require supported housing and assistance with their housing costs will continue to be protected. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans in the autumn.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:48:55.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755633/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755633/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Supported Housing: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people (a) living in supported housing and (b) living in supported housing with a mental illness can pay their rent if the proposed reforms to supported housing funding are introduced.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T14:21:20.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755634/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Housing Benefit: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with a mental illness living in supported housing are in receipt of housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755635","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-20","<p>Tackling social mobility is at the heart of the Government’s ambition to make Britain a country that works for everyone. All homes should be of a reasonable standard and everyone should have a safe place to live. In rented housing, the Government is committed to ensuring tenants enjoy decent standards and receive a service which represents value for money for their rent. Local authorities have strong and effective powers to deal with poor quality, unsafe accommodation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-20T11:19:18.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755635/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755635/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to page 18 of the Social Mobility Commission Report, Time for Change: an assessment of government policies on social mobility 1997-2017, what assessment he has made of the effect of poor housing conditions on social mobility.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755636","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>Licensing is an effective tool when used in a targeted fashion to deliver improved standards and safety in the private rented sector in specific areas that are suffering from serious problems.</p><p>Under Part 3 of the Housing Act 2004, local authorities are able to introduce a selective licensing scheme in defined areas to tackle problems such as deprivation, high crime and poor property conditions.</p><p>Any scheme submitted to the Secretary of State for confirmation will be considered on its merits and whether it meets the statutory requirements in Part 3 of the Housing Act 2004.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","7215","2017-09-13T16:48:47.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755636/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755636/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Landlords: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of borough-wide licensing schemes in tackling criminal landlords.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755637","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>Licensing is an effective tool when used in a targeted fashion to deliver improved standards and safety in the private rented sector in specific areas that are suffering from serious problems.</p><p>Under Part 3 of the Housing Act 2004, local authorities are able to introduce a selective licensing scheme in defined areas to tackle problems such as deprivation, high crime and poor property conditions.</p><p>Any scheme submitted to the Secretary of State for confirmation will be considered on its merits and whether it meets the statutory requirements in Part 3 of the Housing Act 2004.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","7214","2017-09-13T16:48:47.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755637/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755637/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Landlords: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of borough-wide licensing schemes on improving the standard and safety of accommodation in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755638","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>We publish guidance for highway authorities on the design of traffic calming measures, including road humps, in Local Transport Note (LTN) 01/07 ‘Traffic Calming’. This can be viewed via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-transport-notes" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-transport-notes</a></p><p> </p><p>In terms of the use of traffic calming measures including road humps, DfT circular 01/2013 ‘Setting local speed limits’ states that whilst the vast majority of traffic calming measures in use are speed humps, tables, cushions or rumble devices, traffic authorities will want to consider the full set of available measures.</p><p> </p><p>It should also be noted that the revised Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions 2016 add upright speed limit repeaters and road markings to the prescribed list of traffic calming features. These may now be used in addition to the self-enforcing features within signed 20 mph zones, and will enable local authorities to reduce the number of physical traffic calming features where vehicle speed is already around 20 mph due to the nature of the road.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement is now for at least one physical traffic calming feature within a 20 mph zone. Beyond that traffic authorities may, at their discretion, place any combination upright signs, speed limit road markings or additional physical traffic calming features at 100 metre (maximum) intervals. In doing so they will need to carefully consider the implications for the self-enforcing nature of a 20 mph zone.</p><p> </p><p>It is however ultimately for local authorities to decide whether they wish to install or remove road humps.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:36:15.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755638/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755638/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Road Humps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department has published on the removal of speed bumps.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755639","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>The public consultation, ‘Tackling Unfair Practices in the Leasehold Market’, looks at a range of measures to help tackle unfair and unreasonable abuses of the leasehold system. The consultation closes on 19 September 2017. The Government cannot pre-empt the consultation or comment while it is still on going. We will review all responses and respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:38:51.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755639/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755639/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for implementing the ban on new build homes being sold as leasehold.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755640","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>The person undertaking building work is responsible for compliance with the building regulations. All new build housing is subject to supervision by a building control body, who have a legal duty to take all reasonable steps to ascertain if the building work complies with the relevant requirements of the building regulations.</p><p>Local authorities have enforcement powers to order alteration or removal of building work which contravenes the building regulations and bring a prosecution in the Magistrates’ Court for a breach of the building regulations. In 2015 the previous limit on fines for breaches of building regulations was lifted so fines on conviction for breach of the building regulations are now unlimited.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-25T11:32:44.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755640/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755640/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that building safety regulations for new build housing is enforced.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","6944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755641","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-20","<p>Consolidated advice published on 5 September 2017 sets out the results of Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding screening tests and the seven large scale system tests conducted over the summer:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-20T13:14:33.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755641/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755641/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 24 July 2017 to Question 4834, how many of the cladding samples that have been tested would not meet the Department's stated view to meet the Building Regulations requirement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","6959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755642","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>The number of empty homes in England is at its lowest since records began in 2004. In May 2010 over 300,000 homes in England had been standing empty for longer than 6 months. As of October 2016 the number of long-term empty properties had fallen to 200,145. Local authorities have powers and strong incentives to tackle empty homes.</p><ul><li>Through the New Homes Bonus they earn the same financial reward for bringing an empty home back into use as building a new one.</li><li>Councils may also charge up to 150 per cent council tax for homes empty for over two years.</li></ul><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:46:01.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755642/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755642/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Empty Property: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to promote the refurbishment of empty and vacant homes.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","7053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755643","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-21","<p>The private rented sector is an important part of our housing market, housing 4.5 million households in England. The proportion of tenants in the private rented sector living in non-decent housing fell from 47 per cent in 2006 to 28 per cent in 2015. Local authorities have strong and effective powers to deal with poor quality unsafe accommodation and we expect them to use those powers. Under the Housing Act 2004, they can issue an Improvement Notice or a Hazard Awareness Notice if they find a defect in the property. In extreme circumstances, the local authority may prohibit that property from being rented or decide to make repairs themselves and claim the cost back from the landlord.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-21T14:14:58.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755643/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755643/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Private Rented Housing: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that private sector landlords maintain their properties to ensure the safety of their tenants.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","7398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755644","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>As set out in the Housing White Paper - <em>Fixing our broken housing market – </em>we have started work on a review of the cost effectiveness of current energy performance standards for new homes. We will consult on improving the requirements on new homes if evidence suggests that there are opportunities to do so without making homes less affordable for those who want to buy their own home.</p><p>Following the tragic events at Grenfell Tower we must also take into consideration any broader lessons which emerge from Dame Judith Hackett’s independent review of Building Regulations and fire safety to ensure that any proposed new requirements are safe and practical in addition to being cost effective and affordable.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T12:57:01.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755644/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755644/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to ensure that all new homes are built to ultra-low emission standards from 2020.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","7414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755645","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>My Department is working closely with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) which has policy responsibility for energy efficiency measures. From April 2018 The Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property) (England and Wales) Regulations will require private rented sector landlords to improve the worst performing properties to a minimum EPC band E rating before they can be let, subject to certain exemptions. By April 2020, all private rented sector properties must achieve a minimum EPC band E rating, even if there has been no change in the tenancy, subject to certain exemptions.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T14:31:23.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755645/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755645/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to improve energy efficiency in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","7415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755646","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>To source this information would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T12:46:36.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755646/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755646/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many working hours have been spent by civil servants in his Department in response to the Grenfell Tower fire; and what proportion of his Department's civil servants total working hours was spent on that work.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755647","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are determined to ensure that victims get the help they need, when they need it.</p><p>Our Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy is clear that refuges and other forms of specialist accommodation based services play a vital role in supporting victims of domestic abuse to move from danger to safety and independence.</p><p>We have provided £20 million funding to 76 projects in England, creating more than 2,200 bed spaces and giving support to over 19,000 victims. This is in addition to the £13.5 million awarded in 2014/15 and 2015/16 to strengthen refuge and other safe accommodation provision.</p><p>Local areas are best placed to understand local needs and the Government has devolved power and responsibility for meeting those needs accordingly, including to devolved administrations. However, we expect local areas to provide services that are responsive to the needs of victims fleeing from domestic abuse and make decisions on the provision of safe accommodation and support to fit the identified needs for all domestic abuse victims, both those from within and those who flee across local area boundaries. Our Priorities for Domestic Abuse Services reinforce the expectation that local areas should plan to support victims of domestic abuse who have moved to another area to stay safe.</p><p>We are clear in the Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy that we will review this approach after two years. If we are not reassured that women are receiving the support they need, then we will consider if moving to a national model of provision will improve these services for victims.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T13:54:31.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755647/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755647/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Refuges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will place a duty on local authorities to (a) ensure that sufficient places of safety are available for victims of domestic violence and (b) encourage local authorities to have in place reciprocal arrangements so that the issue of victim safety is paramount.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","7463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755648","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>We have asked all owners of buildings over 18 metres with Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding to submit samples to the BRE for screening to establish whether the materials submitted are of limited combustibility. Where samples that are sent in do not meet the limited combustibility test we are also collecting information on what insulation materials have been used.</p><p>Summary advice published on 5 September (available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a>) sets out the results of screening tests and the seven large-scale system tests conducted over the summer, and includes the numbers of these buildings which have the type of insulation used.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:37:26.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755648/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755648/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has estimated how much of insulation used in high-rise and low-rise buildings is (a) polyisocyanurate foam, (b) phenolic foam and (c) mineral wool insulation.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","7453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755649","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government will consider this issue in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going building safety work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:39:01.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755649/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755649/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he will consider a system of binary classification of building cladding material as either combustible or non-combustible.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","7454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755650","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government will consider this issue in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, and on going building safety work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:40:43.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755650/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755650/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Fire Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether it is his policy to maintain the desktop study route for materials to meet fire safety approval.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","7455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755651","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>Smoke development and smoke toxicity is not a feature of either the screening or large-scale tests conducted for DCLG, so was not measured.</p><p>Following a request from DCLG, the Building Research Establishment (BRE) agreed to contact customers for whom they had carried out large-scale testing previously. If a customer gives permission, the BRE provides summary details of the test on their website (<a href="http://www.bre.co.uk/regulatory-testing" target="_blank">www.bre.co.uk/regulatory-testing</a>).</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-13T16:58:15.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755651/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755651/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will require the Building and Research Establishment to (a) report measurement of smoke development and smoke toxicity from the recent post-Grenfell Tower tests it has conducted and (b) publish all past test information results it holds.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","7423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755652","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-29","<p>All residents should understand the emergency fire safety guidance in their buildings. It is building owners' responsibility to ensure that this is the case. The Government has encouraged building owners to communicate with residents with respect to any actions being taken as part of the checking and testing process for Aluminium Composite Material cladding.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-29T09:37:09.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755652/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755652/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 10 July 2017 to Question 2770, what steps are being taken to monitor the provision by local authorities or otherwise of emergency guidance in high-rise blocks in languages spoken by all residents; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","7469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755653","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Northern Ireland Assembly Environment committee made their recommendation to revise wind turbine noise guidelines with a view to considering the noise impact on nearby resident's day to day lives. This issue has been addressed through the written statement covering wind farm applications, made by my Rt Hon Friend Greg Clark MP, the previous Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on 18 June 2015, Official Report, column 9WS: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-06-18/HCWS42/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-06-18/HCWS42/</a></p><p>Only if the applicant is able to demonstrate that the planning impacts identified by the affected local community have been fully addressed, including noise, can the planning authority grant permission.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:42:41.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755653/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755653/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Wind Power: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of adopting the recommendations of the report of the Northern Ireland Assembly's Committee for the Environment of 2015 on wind energy to replace ETSU-R-97 with a method of measuring loudness that brings wind turbine noise controls in line with other industrial controls.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","7525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755654","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>This information is not held centrally. Planning permissions are the responsibility of local planning authorities and as such this information can be requested from the relevant local planning authorities for the geography required.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T10:58:19.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755654/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755654/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Planning Permission: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of approved extant planning permissions in (a) Bury St Edmunds constituency and (b) East Anglia; and what the expiry date for each such planning permission is.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","7502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755655","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety, led by Dame Judith Hackitt, was announced by the government on 28 July 2017.</p><p>The Terms of Reference were published on 30 August. These make clear that the Review will look at other international regulatory systems for buildings and regulatory systems in other sectors with similar safety risks.</p><p>The Review will draw upon international experience of regulatory frameworks and the frameworks covering other industries as it fully recognises the important contribution it will make in eventual recommendations made to the government.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:40:08.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755655/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755655/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will ensure that relevant lessons on fire prevention in high-rise buildings are learned from countries which have a good record of preventing fires in such buildings.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","7514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755656","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government supports the principle of facilitating a Gaining Provider Led (GPL) switching process covering the communications markets, because the process should be led by the organisation with the most interest in making the switch work effectively for the benefit of consumers, the gaining provider. A GPL switching process is already in place for consumers who switch their fixed landline telephone provider across the Openreach network, which covers the vast majority of phone lines within in the UK, taking up to ten working days. The Government is committed to continuing to reduce the potential barriers that may prevent some consumers from deciding to switch, which is why we have ensured that the Digital Economy Act 2017, made explicit Ofcom's power to set general conditions for switching within the communications markets.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-11T08:10:13.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755656/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755656/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Communication: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what her Department's policy is on supporting the introduction of gaining-provider led processes across the communications market set out in the Switching Principles Action Plan of May 2016.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","7526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755657","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-10","<p>It is estimated that the area of West Yorkshire and York will achieve over 96% superfast coverage by the end of March 2018.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-10T11:41:23.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755657/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755657/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress the Government is making against its target to deliver access to superfast broadband to 93 per cent of West Yorkshire by the end of March 2018.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755658","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring universal broadband access to at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind. We are currently considering two options for delivering this: a regulatory USO and a voluntary offer from BT and Openreach.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-14T16:30:06.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755658/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755658/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Universal Service Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether any revisions to the timescale for implementing the broadband universal service obligation have been made since the 2017 General Election.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755659","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>Currently, an estimated 94% of premises in West Yorkshire and York have access to superfast broadband. By the end of the current contract in March 2018, coverage is estimated to increase to over 96%. With UK Government support, West Yorkshire Combined Authority is currently negotiating a contract extension beyond March 2018 which will provide further superfast coverage. For premises not covered by superfast broadband, we will ensure universal broadband coverage of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-04T12:19:13.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755659/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755659/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the timetable is for 100 per cent of residents of West Yorkshire having access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755660","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>None.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-07T16:41:21.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755660/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755660/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","YouTube","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what information her Department holds on the number of paid YouTube contributors in the UK.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","7513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755661","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>No specific assessment has been made of the effect of Exchange Only (EO) lines on businesses operating in the Cricklewood Broadway area.</p><p> </p><p>Upgrading EO lines is more complicated (and more expensive) as there are greater engineering challenges. For instance, because EO lines do not have the copper lines routed through a copper cabinet, there is no aggregation point to which a fibre cabinet can be connected. For these reasons it can take longer for EO lines to be upgraded. Openreach have confirmed this, and have advised that they currently fall outside any commercial rollout. However, they have said there is potential for EO lines to be brought into scope for upgrading through their Community Fibre Partnerships.</p><p>For those that do not see improved connectivity through publicly funded and commercial investment, we will ensure universal broadband coverage of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind</p><p> </p><p>We are keen to ensure even better digital connectivity in the UK. We announced a package of measures worth £1.1 billion at Autumn Statement 2016 to support this:<br></p><ul><li>The Digital Infrastructure Investment Fund, which was launched on 3 July 2017 will provide finance for new fibre investments.</li><li>The Local Full Fibre Networks programme, which will support local bodies in stimulating the market for fibre connectivity in their areas.</li><li>A Bill to enable business rates relief for new fibre build.</li></ul><p>Together, these investments and incentives will stimulate the market to deliver the increase in capacity that is needed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:30:26.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755661/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755661/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Cricklewood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has made an assessment of the effect of limited (Exchange Only) internet speeds on businesses operating in the Cricklewood Broadway area.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","7366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755662","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The government fully recognises the major benefits of holding the British Grand Prix, given its status in the UK sporting calendar and the considerable wider economic opportunities it provides. The British Racing Drivers' Club have kept government informed about their discussions on the future of British Grand Prix, and this dialogue will continue. This is primarily a commercial matter between the British Racing Drivers' Club and Liberty F1 to progress.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-11T10:31:13.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755662/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755662/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Motor Sports: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will take steps to assist with the hosting fees of the British Grand Prix; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","7364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755663","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since the announcement of the Internet Safety Strategy in February, DCMS has been working with a wide range of stakeholders to look at how we can make Britain the safest place in the world for users, including children and young adults, to be online. The Strategy will consider online harms which users can experience on social media. We will be publishing the Strategy with an accompanying consultation shortly.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:34:25.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755663/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755663/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Internet: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent progress has been made on implementing the internet safety strategy; and how that strategy plans to tackle the effects of social media-related mental health issues in young adults.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","7421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755664","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>An estimated 94% of premises in the constituency of Hemsworth currently have access to superfast speeds. By March 2018, this is predicted to rise to 97%. With UK Government support, West Yorkshire Combined Authority is currently negotiating an extension to its current delivery contract which will provide further superfast coverage, and for the remainder we will ensure universal broadband coverage of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-04T12:19:30.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755664/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755664/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Hemsworth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, by what date it is planned that 100 per cent of residents of Hemsworth village will have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755665","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Local authorities in England have a statutory duty under the Public Libraries and Museums Act 1964 (1964 Act) to provide a comprehensive and efficient library service.</p><p>In December 2016, the Taskforce published ‘Libraries Deliver: Ambition for Public Libraries in England 2016-2021’, which sets out a vision for library services in England. The Government is working with the Taskforce to promote good practice and innovation to assist library services and enable them to be sustainable for the long term.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-12T11:15:22.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755665/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755665/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Public Libraries: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the number of local libraries closing.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","7056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755666","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>After the UK leaves the EU, free movement will end but migration between the UK and the EU will continue. The Government has been clear that, in future, the Free Movement Directive will no longer apply, however the UK will remain an open and tolerant country; one that recognises the valuable contribution migrants make to our society and welcomes those with the skills and expertise to make our nation better still. To retain the UK’s position as a world leader in the creative industries, the UK needs to continue to attract the brightest and best, including those from the EU, with high level skills that can support the creative sector, the industrial strategy and benefit the wider UK economy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:07:48.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755666/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755666/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Arts: Free Movement of Labour","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what economic assessment the Government has made of the impact on ending freedom of movement on the creative industries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755667","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>DCMS has had no discussions with the Taiwanese authorities about the display of artworks from the National Palace Museum, Taipei at British museums.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-12T16:41:54.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755667/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755667/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Art Works: Taiwan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Taiwanese Government to display works of art from the National Palace Museum of Taiwan in British museums.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","6956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755668","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department has contributed £50.8 million to the current Highlands &amp; Islands broadband project and £50 million to the project for the Rest of Scotland. A further £20.99 million has been allocated to support further Rollout by Digital Scotland across both projects which could include Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk. For premises not covered by superfast broadband, we will ensure universal broadband coverage of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:27:17.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755668/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755668/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how she plans to improve access to broadband services in Berwickshire Roxburgh and Selkirk.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","7140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755669","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>We are determined to ensure even better digital connectivity right across the UK. We are focused on improving, and future-proofing, the country's digital infrastructure, with a particular focus on full fibre connectivity.</p><p>We have previously announced a package of measures worth £1.1 billion at Autumn Statement 2016 to support this:</p><ul><li>The Digital Infrastructure Investment Fund, which was launched on 3 July 2017 will provide finance for new fibre investments.</li><li>The Local Full Fibre Networks programme, which will support local bodies in stimulating the market for fibre connectivity in their areas.</li><li>A Bill to enable business rates relief for new fibre build.</li></ul><p>Together, these investments and incentives will stimulate the market to deliver the increase in capacity that is needed.</p><p>For those that do not see improved connectivity through publicly funded and commercial investment, we will ensure universal broadband coverage of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-14T16:45:29.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755669/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755669/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress her Department has made on the provision of fibre optic broadband for exchange-only telephone lines.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","7113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755670","Department for Education","false","2017-09-21","<p>We know that the creative industries are a cultural and economic success story for the UK being worth £87.4bn to UK economy in 2015 and growing by more than a third since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The new National Curriculum was developed with input from employers and representatives from both the further and higher education sectors. It was designed to equip pupils with the knowledge they need to progress either into further education or to make a successful start on their careers, including roles in the creative industries.</p><p> </p><p>The total proportion of pupils finishing Key Stage 4 who were entered into a GCSE in an arts subjects rose between 2012 and 2015, but fell slightly in 2016. Comparable data is not yet available for 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-21T09:45:10.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755670/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755670/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Arts: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of changes in the number of people studying arts subjects in schools on the effectiveness of UK creative industries.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","7112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755671","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Local authorities are responsible for funding and providing public library services in England, and made net investment of £701 million in 2015/16. The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) has additionally provided funding support for library authorities throughout England. This included funding a £2.6 million programme to support the installation or upgrade of wifi in public libraries in England; benefitting around 1,000 libraries, and enabling over 99% of public libraries to offer free wifi. DCMS also financed the £3.9m Libraries: Opportunities for Everyone fund to support innovative library service activity to benefit disadvantaged people and places in England. The Government will continue to encourage local authorities to invest in libraries to ensure that they remain relevant and meet the needs of the community.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","7808","2017-09-11T12:22:32.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755671/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755671/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much funding her Department will provide to local authorities in England to maintain and run libraries in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","7055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755672","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State for the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) has regular discussions with ministerial colleagues on a range of issues affecting the creative industries, including the impacts and opportunities presented by the UK’s exit from the EU.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:10:02.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755672/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755672/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Arts: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for the Home Department on the provision of short-term work visas for EU residents in the creative industries wishing to do project work in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755673","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are working closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","7069","2017-09-12T16:05:06.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755673/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755673/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will conduct an audit of EU funding to the UK creative sector.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755674","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are working closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","7068","2017-09-12T16:05:06.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755674/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755674/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has made to replace EU funding to the UK creative sector once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755675","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The government's sport strategy sets out our plans to get more people active, in particular in under-represented groups, including women.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England’s This Girl Can campaign, and other initiatives, have helped to narrow the gender gap in sport participation. Results from the Active Lives survey, published earlier this year, showed that 59% of women and 63% of men had done at least 150 minutes of physical activity a week, the amount of activity recommended for adults by the Chief Medical Officer.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-12T16:43:18.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755675/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755675/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Sports: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will bring forward proposals to ensure more women are encouraged into sport.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755676","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer the hon member to my response to the question from the member from Orkney and Shetland during DCMS questions today in the chamber.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","900848","2017-09-14T16:58:48.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755676/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755676/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much her Department has contributed to the Digital Scotland Superfast Broadband programme; and what other support her Department has given to the rollout of superfast broadband in Scotland.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","7202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755677","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Currently there is an estimated 12,300 premises in Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk which do not have access to superfast broadband from either a commercial or publicly funded programme. This means over 75% of the constituency can access superfast broadband, up from below 5% in 2010.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:25:45.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755677/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755677/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many properties in Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk are estimated not to have access to superfast broadband services.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","7141"
